00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:25.200
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
So let's get started today.

00:00:25.200 --> 00:00:28.820
Again, the topic is fare policy,
structure, and technology.

00:00:28.820 --> 00:00:32.420
So we'll cover policy
objectives, the issues

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:35.140
that agencies face,
fare structure,

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:39.150
demand response to fare
changes and fare technology.

00:00:39.150 --> 00:00:41.810
So what are the
objectives of fare policy?

00:00:45.860 --> 00:00:49.850
There are multiple objectives,
and they don't necessarily

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:50.930
support each other.

00:00:50.930 --> 00:00:52.680
In fact, they often
go against each other.

00:00:52.680 --> 00:00:56.340
So the number one objective
is to fund operations.

00:00:56.340 --> 00:01:01.250
That's the reason there's
a user fee for service.

00:01:01.250 --> 00:01:02.660
And I say here at
least partially

00:01:02.660 --> 00:01:05.840
because for the most part,
the revenues obtained

00:01:05.840 --> 00:01:09.290
by fare collection do not cover
the full operational costs,

00:01:09.290 --> 00:01:11.280
let alone capital costs.

00:01:11.280 --> 00:01:14.990
So here we have some examples
of fare recovery ratios

00:01:14.990 --> 00:01:18.965
based on the 2014
National Transit Database.

00:01:18.965 --> 00:01:20.660
Now, you might
remember that we talked

00:01:20.660 --> 00:01:22.310
about the National
Transit Database

00:01:22.310 --> 00:01:23.870
earlier in this course.

00:01:23.870 --> 00:01:26.370
And here is a breakdown.

00:01:26.370 --> 00:01:28.940
I looked at all
heavy rail and I saw

00:01:28.940 --> 00:01:31.770
a range of between 0.14 0.78.

00:01:31.770 --> 00:01:35.525
So between 14% and 78%
of operational expenses

00:01:35.525 --> 00:01:39.260
are covered by fare revenue.

00:01:39.260 --> 00:01:42.500
The highest one here
is in California.

00:01:42.500 --> 00:01:47.327
For light rail a little lower
and for bus all over the place.

00:01:47.327 --> 00:01:48.410
Here we have the averages.

00:01:48.410 --> 00:01:52.880
These tend to be higher
for rail and lower for bus.

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:55.130
So why is that?

00:01:55.130 --> 00:01:57.044
Why would that be the case?

00:01:57.044 --> 00:01:58.460
AUDIENCE: On an
operational level,

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:02.270
one rail driver is carrying
a lot more passengers

00:02:02.270 --> 00:02:03.919
than one bus driver.

00:02:03.919 --> 00:02:05.210
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:02:05.210 --> 00:02:12.684
Although you can
fill up a bus, right?

00:02:12.684 --> 00:02:15.100
AUDIENCE: You can fill up a
bus [INAUDIBLE] train carrying

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:15.770
500 passengers.

00:02:15.770 --> 00:02:16.160
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:02:16.160 --> 00:02:17.270
Yeah.

00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:17.820
Yeah.

00:02:17.820 --> 00:02:19.560
Yeah.

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:25.020
So to sort of go
back to my rebuttal,

00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:29.010
there are some buzzers here with
fare recovery ratios over one.

00:02:29.010 --> 00:02:34.370
So it's possible to have a bus
service that returns profit

00:02:34.370 --> 00:02:35.100
even.

00:02:35.100 --> 00:02:40.020
So why is it that
system-wide, bus services

00:02:40.020 --> 00:02:42.960
tend to have lower
fare recovery ratios?

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:45.390
Because you have a good point,
the productivity of rail

00:02:45.390 --> 00:02:46.710
can be higher.

00:02:46.710 --> 00:02:49.680
Of course, if rail
is underutilized,

00:02:49.680 --> 00:02:51.660
then you still have that issue.

00:02:51.660 --> 00:02:53.040
Any other ideas?

00:02:53.040 --> 00:02:54.324
[INAUDIBLE]

00:02:54.324 --> 00:02:58.140
AUDIENCE: Buses [INAUDIBLE]
who can have the most service

00:02:58.140 --> 00:03:01.587
and cover the most
low ridership routes?

00:03:01.587 --> 00:03:02.920
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Right.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:05.110
So there's an agency
and you system-wide

00:03:05.110 --> 00:03:07.360
have to cover your territory.

00:03:07.360 --> 00:03:11.590
That will include buses that
are not very heavily utilized.

00:03:11.590 --> 00:03:13.521
Also, you're
providing service late

00:03:13.521 --> 00:03:14.770
at night and all those things.

00:03:14.770 --> 00:03:19.540
So there are many cases of buses
not being very well utilized,

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:22.180
and that brings down
the fare recovery ratio.

00:03:22.180 --> 00:03:24.650
I did not include here
demand responsive.

00:03:24.650 --> 00:03:30.250
Demand responsive is
usually around 1% to 2%.

00:03:30.250 --> 00:03:32.680
So I'm talking about
what here in Boston

00:03:32.680 --> 00:03:38.080
is called the ride for
disabled passengers.

00:03:38.080 --> 00:03:43.360
And it can cost
around $20 per ride,

00:03:43.360 --> 00:03:44.920
and people pay a lot less.

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:48.897
So I think $20 is low.

00:03:48.897 --> 00:03:49.730
I think it's higher.

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:50.450
Sorry.

00:03:50.450 --> 00:03:53.060
I don't remember the number,
but it's closer to $30 or $40,

00:03:53.060 --> 00:03:54.990
I think.

00:03:54.990 --> 00:03:59.630
So the fare recovery ratio
for demand responsive transit

00:03:59.630 --> 00:04:00.870
is much lower.

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:01.370
OK.

00:04:01.370 --> 00:04:02.840
So other goals.

00:04:02.840 --> 00:04:05.640
Keep transit affordable
and promote social equity.

00:04:05.640 --> 00:04:07.940
So here we have the
first conflicts, right?

00:04:07.940 --> 00:04:11.030
The first objective would mean
that you want to raise fares,

00:04:11.030 --> 00:04:14.000
and if you raise fares then
you get more fare revenue.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:15.500
But there's another
objective, which

00:04:15.500 --> 00:04:18.410
is to keep transit affordable
and for social equity,

00:04:18.410 --> 00:04:21.019
and that would indicate that
you want to keep fares low.

00:04:21.019 --> 00:04:22.850
Right?

00:04:22.850 --> 00:04:26.780
So also, supporting growth
for demand of transit

00:04:26.780 --> 00:04:29.630
also keeps fares low.

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:32.180
Make the fare structure
easy to communicate.

00:04:32.180 --> 00:04:35.060
We'll talk about different
fare structures and market

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:37.050
segmentation later
in this lecture.

00:04:37.050 --> 00:04:40.880
But the point is that when
you do market segmentation,

00:04:40.880 --> 00:04:45.560
you can get more revenue
out of your fare system.

00:04:45.560 --> 00:04:47.420
When you want to
keep things simple,

00:04:47.420 --> 00:04:50.300
then you're probably going to
suggest going for a flat fare

00:04:50.300 --> 00:04:53.900
structure, where people that
have much higher willingness

00:04:53.900 --> 00:04:56.120
to pay are still
paying low fares.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:59.240
So that objective
of keeping the fare

00:04:59.240 --> 00:05:02.090
structure easy to
communicate and simple

00:05:02.090 --> 00:05:04.670
will reduce fare earnings.

00:05:04.670 --> 00:05:07.170
And finally, to reduce
fare system costs.

00:05:07.170 --> 00:05:10.640
So there are costs
to fare collection

00:05:10.640 --> 00:05:12.650
and to the fare
system as a whole.

00:05:12.650 --> 00:05:13.950
Fare collection is one of them.

00:05:13.950 --> 00:05:18.440
So obviously, the capital cost
of installing the fare boxes

00:05:18.440 --> 00:05:21.770
and maintaining the
whole AFC system.

00:05:21.770 --> 00:05:24.800
There is a cost for people
who are maintaining those fare

00:05:24.800 --> 00:05:29.000
boxes and vaulting cash
out of the fare boxes

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:32.630
and counting the cash and
keeping it in a safe place.

00:05:32.630 --> 00:05:33.950
And there's customer service.

00:05:33.950 --> 00:05:37.940
So customer service involves
more than the fare system.

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:39.830
But some aspects
of customer service

00:05:39.830 --> 00:05:44.750
involve my CharlieCard doesn't
work, can I get a new one?

00:05:44.750 --> 00:05:47.510
Or I already paid
for that ride and you

00:05:47.510 --> 00:05:49.260
need to give me a refund.

00:05:49.260 --> 00:05:53.930
So these kinds of
inquiries or complaints

00:05:53.930 --> 00:05:56.900
are coming from the fare system.

00:05:56.900 --> 00:05:57.400
OK?

00:05:57.400 --> 00:06:01.060
Questions about
these objectives?

00:06:01.060 --> 00:06:01.560
No.

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:02.360
OK.

00:06:02.360 --> 00:06:05.770
So how does fare policy
intersect with other areas?

00:06:05.770 --> 00:06:08.400
It intersects with many areas,
and that makes fare policy

00:06:08.400 --> 00:06:12.530
and fare structure a very
powerful sort of lever or knob

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.170
for a transit agency.

00:06:15.170 --> 00:06:17.390
So obviously, finance.

00:06:17.390 --> 00:06:19.400
We're talking about funding
operational expenses

00:06:19.400 --> 00:06:22.520
from the revenues derived
from the fare system.

00:06:22.520 --> 00:06:23.820
And then there's operations.

00:06:23.820 --> 00:06:29.630
So if you have a fare policy
that makes people board faster

00:06:29.630 --> 00:06:32.100
because, for example,
it's proof of payments

00:06:32.100 --> 00:06:33.920
so there's no
validation required

00:06:33.920 --> 00:06:37.790
or you have fare technology
that a smart card is

00:06:37.790 --> 00:06:40.820
much faster than
paying cash, then

00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:43.340
that means that you'll have
faster boarding, shorter dwell

00:06:43.340 --> 00:06:46.430
times, shorter cycle
times, higher reliability.

00:06:46.430 --> 00:06:51.800
So you might affect operations
through fare technology.

00:06:51.800 --> 00:06:54.470
Some fare structures
require fare inspection.

00:06:54.470 --> 00:06:58.070
So proof of payment is
one that people board

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:00.570
without interacting
with any fare system,

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:02.490
so then an inspector
has to come in

00:07:02.490 --> 00:07:06.140
and either for all
passengers or more likely

00:07:06.140 --> 00:07:09.320
for a subset of passengers, a
sample of passengers, request

00:07:09.320 --> 00:07:12.350
proof of having paid the fare.

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:15.680
And of course, that
involves some cost.

00:07:15.680 --> 00:07:17.096
There's maintenance
of equipment.

00:07:17.096 --> 00:07:18.470
If equipment breaks
down, the bus

00:07:18.470 --> 00:07:22.220
needs to be taken out
of service, et cetera.

00:07:22.220 --> 00:07:23.130
Public support.

00:07:23.130 --> 00:07:26.990
So politicians may
promise not raising fares.

00:07:26.990 --> 00:07:28.812
That's a popular
campaign promise.

00:07:28.812 --> 00:07:30.770
And then of course, that
puts a lot of pressure

00:07:30.770 --> 00:07:33.650
on the agency to
do more with less.

00:07:33.650 --> 00:07:36.140
And we'll talk more
about that when

00:07:36.140 --> 00:07:38.820
we discuss transit finance.

00:07:38.820 --> 00:07:42.230
There's difficulty gathering
support to raise fares.

00:07:42.230 --> 00:07:45.190
Usually, we'll
improve service first

00:07:45.190 --> 00:07:47.580
and then that justifies
raising fares.

00:07:47.580 --> 00:07:48.080
Right?

00:07:48.080 --> 00:07:50.060
I don't want my service
to get more expensive

00:07:50.060 --> 00:07:52.956
if it's not very good service.

00:07:52.956 --> 00:07:54.937
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:07:54.937 --> 00:07:56.270
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Right.

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:59.270
And essentially, if you
have lower service quality,

00:07:59.270 --> 00:08:01.761
then fewer people end up
taking it or liking it,

00:08:01.761 --> 00:08:03.260
and those people
are not going to be

00:08:03.260 --> 00:08:09.260
the ones rallying for a
transit sort of fare hike.

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:11.627
Then there's also labor's
push for higher wages.

00:08:11.627 --> 00:08:13.460
So that's another sort
of political pressure

00:08:13.460 --> 00:08:17.090
on the agency that
increases operational costs

00:08:17.090 --> 00:08:20.360
and therefore, may require
an increase in fares.

00:08:20.360 --> 00:08:24.140
But both a labor
dispute and a dispute

00:08:24.140 --> 00:08:26.900
with the passengers
on the fare hike

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:32.210
are the result of unpleasant
negotiations or interactions

00:08:32.210 --> 00:08:33.770
in public.

00:08:33.770 --> 00:08:36.907
Administration, so fare
technology and fare policy

00:08:36.907 --> 00:08:37.740
and equity analysis.

00:08:37.740 --> 00:08:41.750
If you're considering any
change to technology or policy

00:08:41.750 --> 00:08:45.020
or structure, you have to
analyze the economic aspects

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:51.170
of it and you have to
prove that you're not

00:08:51.170 --> 00:08:54.850
discriminating against any one
group, even unintentionally.

00:08:54.850 --> 00:08:58.430
So disproportionately affecting
a disadvantaged community,

00:08:58.430 --> 00:09:05.480
either by race or income, that's
called Title VI in the US.

00:09:05.480 --> 00:09:07.850
Then there's another
big policy issue

00:09:07.850 --> 00:09:10.160
is revenue sharing
across jurisdictions.

00:09:10.160 --> 00:09:14.840
Not so much an issue on the east
coast of the US, but certainly

00:09:14.840 --> 00:09:18.590
if you go to the West Coast, you
have in the San Francisco Bay

00:09:18.590 --> 00:09:22.050
Area dozens of operators.

00:09:22.050 --> 00:09:24.180
Some of them share
the same fare system.

00:09:24.180 --> 00:09:29.570
So how much does
each operator pay

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:32.780
for routes that serve
multiple jurisdictions?

00:09:32.780 --> 00:09:36.410
That's one question.

00:09:36.410 --> 00:09:39.760
The other question might be,
if we are separate operators

00:09:39.760 --> 00:09:42.710
and we each have a route
so we take care of that,

00:09:42.710 --> 00:09:46.430
we still are collecting
fares with a joint system.

00:09:46.430 --> 00:09:47.780
Do we trust each other?

00:09:47.780 --> 00:09:51.530
And often, actually, the
barriers to integration

00:09:51.530 --> 00:09:55.770
are more about trust and
less about technology.

00:09:55.770 --> 00:09:57.904
Marketing is another
sort of issue

00:09:57.904 --> 00:09:59.070
the agency has to deal with.

00:09:59.070 --> 00:10:02.640
How much do they market
and what is the message?

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.460
And customer service,
which we already mentioned.

00:10:05.460 --> 00:10:07.260
It's interesting
to note that fares

00:10:07.260 --> 00:10:09.390
are one of the first
things that a person

00:10:09.390 --> 00:10:11.901
has to sort of understand
about a transit system

00:10:11.901 --> 00:10:12.900
to be able to take them.

00:10:12.900 --> 00:10:15.160
So if you're a tourist
and you go to a new city

00:10:15.160 --> 00:10:17.670
that you've never been to
before you arrive at the airport

00:10:17.670 --> 00:10:20.430
and you want to take the bus
or the train from the airport,

00:10:20.430 --> 00:10:21.804
the first thing
you have to do is

00:10:21.804 --> 00:10:24.240
buy a ticket, right, and
figure out the fare structure

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:27.570
and where are the
maps and et cetera.

00:10:27.570 --> 00:10:30.840
So this is sort of one
of the first issues,

00:10:30.840 --> 00:10:33.450
the first impression that a
passenger has about the fare

00:10:33.450 --> 00:10:36.390
system, about the
transit agency, something

00:10:36.390 --> 00:10:39.720
related to the fare system.

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:40.220
OK.

00:10:40.220 --> 00:10:44.800
What issues do agencies
face regarding these topics?

00:10:44.800 --> 00:10:46.420
One is fare recovery ratios.

00:10:46.420 --> 00:10:48.390
So we looked at ranges.

00:10:48.390 --> 00:10:50.790
Typically, fare recovery
ratio system-wide across modes

00:10:50.790 --> 00:10:52.200
is about 1/3.

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:54.940
It varies a lot, as we saw.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:57.160
It's rare to make
a profit system.

00:10:57.160 --> 00:11:00.120
So one of the
issues is how much--

00:11:00.120 --> 00:11:03.030
well, the first question is, how
much of a fare recovery ratio

00:11:03.030 --> 00:11:09.720
do we need or do we set a goal
to cover operational expenses?

00:11:09.720 --> 00:11:12.930
And is it sort of a
strong requirement,

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:14.420
as it is in some agencies?

00:11:14.420 --> 00:11:18.540
Some agencies have laws that
say the fare recovery ratio must

00:11:18.540 --> 00:11:19.950
be at least this much.

00:11:19.950 --> 00:11:24.270
So if expenses go up,
automatic fare hike.

00:11:24.270 --> 00:11:28.640
Others, it's more of a guideline
or maybe there is no policy.

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:31.150
So that that's one
of the key issues.

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:33.630
The second one is how
often to raise fares.

00:11:33.630 --> 00:11:36.270
I think most agencies
are reactive.

00:11:36.270 --> 00:11:38.370
So a reactive
approach is one where

00:11:38.370 --> 00:11:41.220
you avoid the headache
of a fare hike

00:11:41.220 --> 00:11:46.110
and all the sort of public
engagement that goes with it

00:11:46.110 --> 00:11:49.590
and you only do that
when you have to so

00:11:49.590 --> 00:11:54.600
you are in a financial
situation where you absolutely

00:11:54.600 --> 00:11:59.880
need to raise fare revenues
to continue operating.

00:11:59.880 --> 00:12:03.370
So that happens less
than once every year

00:12:03.370 --> 00:12:05.280
and it's a big effort.

00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:08.400
Some agencies take the
approach of an annual fare

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:10.196
hike with inflation.

00:12:10.196 --> 00:12:11.820
So it's kind of
predictable, it happens

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.380
every year at the same date.

00:12:13.380 --> 00:12:16.590
It tends to make each
one easier than one

00:12:16.590 --> 00:12:20.160
done ad hoc because
it's more expectable

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:23.420
and there's less public outrage.

00:12:26.222 --> 00:12:28.180
So gathering and maintaining
political support,

00:12:28.180 --> 00:12:30.910
we talked a little
bit about that.

00:12:30.910 --> 00:12:35.270
Of course, that is an issue that
will play out and sort of it

00:12:35.270 --> 00:12:40.570
will affect how other issues
are faced and dealt with.

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:43.030
One other issue is do
we raise base fares

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:47.680
or do we change the relative
cost of passes and discounted

00:12:47.680 --> 00:12:48.980
fare products?

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:52.300
So if a base fare
is $2, you might

00:12:52.300 --> 00:12:57.610
have 50% subsidy
for seniors and you

00:12:57.610 --> 00:13:01.570
might have some other discounts
for students or other groups.

00:13:01.570 --> 00:13:04.600
You might also have passes
like a weekly pass, which

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:07.210
if you take some number
of trips you break even

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:09.160
and after that, you ride free.

00:13:09.160 --> 00:13:12.880
So you might actually leave
the base fare the same

00:13:12.880 --> 00:13:17.350
and change the percentages
of subsidy or discounts

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:20.020
or the break even
point of a pass.

00:13:20.020 --> 00:13:21.550
And that can affect
fare revenues,

00:13:21.550 --> 00:13:24.010
it can affect ridership, and
it can affect people's choice

00:13:24.010 --> 00:13:25.700
of fare product.

00:13:25.700 --> 00:13:32.980
So you might bump people towards
letting go of fare passes

00:13:32.980 --> 00:13:37.480
and opting to do pay as you
go more often or the other way

00:13:37.480 --> 00:13:38.240
around.

00:13:38.240 --> 00:13:39.910
And that has implications
on how people

00:13:39.910 --> 00:13:45.520
think about the transit system,
how much it costs for them.

00:13:45.520 --> 00:13:49.330
For a pass holder, of course,
once they've paid for it,

00:13:49.330 --> 00:13:52.630
it's kind of a
non-salient expense.

00:13:52.630 --> 00:13:55.350
So you don't think
about it every time

00:13:55.350 --> 00:13:59.770
you're tapping as much as having
value deducted from the card

00:13:59.770 --> 00:14:00.280
every time.

00:14:00.280 --> 00:14:04.732
So those people might
ride opportunistically

00:14:04.732 --> 00:14:06.190
because they've
already paid for it

00:14:06.190 --> 00:14:09.460
and they might do shorter
trips, discretionary trips

00:14:09.460 --> 00:14:11.680
more so than someone
who is paying

00:14:11.680 --> 00:14:14.524
every fare independently.

00:14:14.524 --> 00:14:15.940
And another big
issue is investing

00:14:15.940 --> 00:14:17.050
in new fare technology.

00:14:17.050 --> 00:14:19.090
That's a headache,
a big headache.

00:14:19.090 --> 00:14:23.610
You can imagine changing the
way the old technology, all

00:14:23.610 --> 00:14:28.090
the analytics and administration
depends on uncertain system.

00:14:28.090 --> 00:14:31.840
And bringing in a new system
that nobody understands yet

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:33.410
might work or not.

00:14:33.410 --> 00:14:36.220
So all the maintenance
needs to be figured out.

00:14:36.220 --> 00:14:39.310
And you have to communicate with
the public about what impact

00:14:39.310 --> 00:14:42.760
that has on them, and
that could involve changes

00:14:42.760 --> 00:14:45.760
in the fare structure,
not just the technology.

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:48.820
So sometimes technology enables
new fare structures or new fare

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:49.890
policies.

00:14:49.890 --> 00:14:51.400
And that can be
one of the reasons

00:14:51.400 --> 00:14:54.130
for bringing new technology.

00:14:54.130 --> 00:14:55.844
Questions on the issues?

00:14:55.844 --> 00:14:56.475
[INAUDIBLE]

