00:16:35.135 --> 00:16:36.760
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
I'm not sure.

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:38.260
Frankly, I'm not sure.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:43.210
Sort of the issues related
to concessions in that case

00:16:43.210 --> 00:16:45.700
depend a lot on the
contract structure.

00:16:45.700 --> 00:16:52.300
So some concessions derive
revenue from the fare.

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:55.400
I think that's not the
best way of doing it.

00:16:55.400 --> 00:16:57.370
But if that's how the
contract is structured,

00:16:57.370 --> 00:16:59.930
essentially, you say,
I want you to operate.

00:16:59.930 --> 00:17:01.870
You keep the fares.

00:17:01.870 --> 00:17:06.430
Then of course, any fare
question will affect revenues

00:17:06.430 --> 00:17:09.250
and it will affect
ridership too.

00:17:09.250 --> 00:17:13.510
So the private operator will be
interested in any kind of fare

00:17:13.510 --> 00:17:16.900
policy change if that
increases their revenues

00:17:16.900 --> 00:17:22.210
and will be disinterested in
any fare policy change that

00:17:22.210 --> 00:17:24.760
decreases their revenues, or
increases the risk of revenue

00:17:24.760 --> 00:17:25.260
anyway.

00:17:25.260 --> 00:17:28.750
So that is probably
a poisonous topic

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:30.640
during the length of
a contract and you

00:17:30.640 --> 00:17:34.780
might have to then do
it between contracts.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:37.090
Here I'm speculating,
but I imagine

00:17:37.090 --> 00:17:42.800
this is a case where you
pay to run by distance

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.070
or you might have some
performance standards as well,

00:17:45.070 --> 00:17:46.660
but it's not fare so much.

00:17:46.660 --> 00:17:48.580
So the government
keeps the fares

00:17:48.580 --> 00:17:51.490
and then pays the operators
the contracted amount.

00:17:51.490 --> 00:17:56.770
Then that disconnects the
operator's performance

00:17:56.770 --> 00:18:00.820
from fare revenue and it allows
the government or the planning

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:06.140
agency to change the fare
structure, change fare

00:18:06.140 --> 00:18:08.960
technology in the
middle of a contract.

00:18:08.960 --> 00:18:12.370
And so in the former case, I
imagine it's quite complicated.

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:19.420
Because usually, the contracts
are not awarded on cycle, i.e.,

00:18:19.420 --> 00:18:22.000
at a certain moment in time
you might have a contract that

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:25.100
expires next month; another
one that expires in a year;

00:18:25.100 --> 00:18:27.010
another one that
expires in five years.

00:18:27.010 --> 00:18:29.710
So to implement a
system-wide change,

00:18:29.710 --> 00:18:32.010
it would be very
difficult if the contracts

00:18:32.010 --> 00:18:34.945
depend on the fare revenues.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:38.536
