00:21:09.210 --> 00:21:11.690
Fare structure, so
market segmentation.

00:21:11.690 --> 00:21:13.580
That's a good segue
with these questions.

00:21:13.580 --> 00:21:17.580
So one possible way of
having a fare structure

00:21:17.580 --> 00:21:19.230
is to have a flat
fare structure.

00:21:19.230 --> 00:21:20.690
That's the simplest one.

00:21:20.690 --> 00:21:23.970
It costs some amount to
ride, no matter what.

00:21:23.970 --> 00:21:26.390
No matter where from,
what time of day,

00:21:26.390 --> 00:21:29.190
what mode, that's the price.

00:21:29.190 --> 00:21:30.950
So again, that's the simplest.

00:21:30.950 --> 00:21:33.230
I think most
agencies, if you look

00:21:33.230 --> 00:21:35.480
at the profile of all
agencies, including small ones,

00:21:35.480 --> 00:21:36.980
have that fare structure.

00:21:36.980 --> 00:21:40.070
Bigger agencies tend to have
some market segmentation

00:21:40.070 --> 00:21:46.460
because they are bigger and they
serve a wider range of people,

00:21:46.460 --> 00:21:48.530
they serve a wider
geographic area,

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:50.670
and they have some
congestion problems.

00:21:50.670 --> 00:21:52.880
So how can we
differentiate fare,

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:54.620
how can we segment the market?

00:21:54.620 --> 00:21:56.160
One is spatially.

00:21:56.160 --> 00:22:00.650
So you could have a flat
geographic structure

00:22:00.650 --> 00:22:04.250
where no matter where you
ride from, it costs the same.

00:22:04.250 --> 00:22:05.510
You could have zones.

00:22:05.510 --> 00:22:11.870
So here in Boston, we have no
zones outside of commuter rail.

00:22:11.870 --> 00:22:13.200
We have no zones.

00:22:13.200 --> 00:22:17.660
When you go to London, there's
zones one through nine,

00:22:17.660 --> 00:22:21.630
but most of the greater London
is in the first three, about.

00:22:21.630 --> 00:22:28.430
So it costs more to cross zones
than to ride within a zone.

00:22:28.430 --> 00:22:34.110
And you can buy passes that are
zone 1, zone 1-2, et cetera.

00:22:34.110 --> 00:22:36.770
So that's one way of doing it.

00:22:36.770 --> 00:22:40.880
If you take that to the extreme
and imagine many, many zones,

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:43.790
you could end up with something
called distance-based pricing,

00:22:43.790 --> 00:22:46.400
where each of the pair
has a different fare,

00:22:46.400 --> 00:22:51.580
depending on how
long that ride was.

00:22:51.580 --> 00:22:55.090
So you can do that if you
have a tap-in, tap-out system,

00:22:55.090 --> 00:22:58.060
you can do that with proof
of payment in some cases.

00:22:58.060 --> 00:23:01.480
It's more common in Europe.

00:23:01.480 --> 00:23:04.270
And regarding zones,
a lot of agencies

00:23:04.270 --> 00:23:06.520
used to have more
zones and are going

00:23:06.520 --> 00:23:09.370
for reducing zones and
simplifying the system.

00:23:09.370 --> 00:23:11.890
It's an interesting,
curious trend

00:23:11.890 --> 00:23:14.920
because they've been doing
this at the same time

00:23:14.920 --> 00:23:17.350
that they've been investing
in new fare technology that

00:23:17.350 --> 00:23:20.920
enables more complex
fare structures.

00:23:20.920 --> 00:23:23.920
But it's a choice of
communicating to the public

00:23:23.920 --> 00:23:26.920
and keeping it simple,
easier to understand.

00:23:26.920 --> 00:23:29.350
AUDIENCE: And do a couple
of years' long advertising

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:30.850
campaign to get
