00:25:08.110 --> 00:25:11.260
it gets canceled
with a timestamp.

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:15.160
And if a fare inspector
comes, you better have one.

00:25:15.160 --> 00:25:17.840
Otherwise, you'll
be heavily fined.

00:25:17.840 --> 00:25:20.170
So that's one way of doing it.

00:25:23.190 --> 00:25:24.870
Any other questions?

00:25:24.870 --> 00:25:25.510
OK.

00:25:25.510 --> 00:25:28.370
Temporal segmentation, so
that's pretty straightforward.

00:25:28.370 --> 00:25:30.160
You've got a flat
system where there

00:25:30.160 --> 00:25:33.100
is no change in fares
across time of day

00:25:33.100 --> 00:25:35.890
and another one where
you have a peak surcharge

00:25:35.890 --> 00:25:37.300
or an off-peak discount.

00:25:37.300 --> 00:25:39.700
Same thing, two ways
of marketing it.

00:25:39.700 --> 00:25:43.390
Most agencies prefer to
offer a discount on off-peak

00:25:43.390 --> 00:25:46.090
than to charge more
during the peak,

00:25:46.090 --> 00:25:48.350
but it's all psychological.

00:25:48.350 --> 00:25:51.640
So why would an agency
be interested in doing

00:25:51.640 --> 00:25:55.090
this and what are the impacts?

