alternatives that they--

00:26:04.300 --> 00:26:05.508
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: OK.

00:26:05.508 --> 00:26:10.270
So nudging people who can
do off-peak to do off-peak

00:26:10.270 --> 00:26:13.300
rather than during the peak.

00:26:13.300 --> 00:26:14.120
What else?

00:26:14.120 --> 00:26:17.040
Any other ideas?

00:26:17.040 --> 00:26:19.250
AUDIENCE: Just encourage
more off-peak ridership

00:26:19.250 --> 00:26:21.476
in general, like people
should probably do this.

00:26:21.476 --> 00:26:21.718
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Right.

00:26:21.718 --> 00:26:23.310
So more discretionary trips.

00:26:23.310 --> 00:26:26.331
So encourage more
off-peak ridership.

00:26:26.331 --> 00:26:26.830
OK.

00:26:26.830 --> 00:26:29.200
And why does it make
sense to charge more

00:26:29.200 --> 00:26:31.690
during the peak than
off-peak, regardless

00:26:31.690 --> 00:26:33.492
of how you market it?

00:26:33.492 --> 00:26:35.436
AUDIENCE: Some people
are [INAUDIBLE] flexible

00:26:35.436 --> 00:26:38.484
in their schedules and
[INAUDIBLE] capture that.

00:26:38.484 --> 00:26:39.900
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Exactly.

00:26:39.900 --> 00:26:41.850
So willingness to
pay is higher, either

00:26:41.850 --> 00:26:43.230
because they are
actually willing

00:26:43.230 --> 00:26:45.600
or because they are
captured on time like they

00:26:45.600 --> 00:26:49.350
have to arrive at some
time to work so they

00:26:49.350 --> 00:26:50.520
don't have many options.

00:26:50.520 --> 00:26:53.760
And that means that
they're much less flexible

00:26:53.760 --> 00:26:58.960
and that their response will be
much lower to a price change.

00:26:58.960 --> 00:27:01.340
OK.

00:27:01.340 --> 00:27:03.880
By service, that's
pretty simple too.

00:27:03.880 --> 00:27:05.630
You could charge the
same for bus and rail

00:27:05.630 --> 00:27:07.850
or you could say rail is
a better service so it's

00:27:07.850 --> 00:27:09.120
going to be more expensive.

00:27:09.120 --> 00:27:10.910
The MBTA has this option.

00:27:10.910 --> 00:27:13.970
Regular bus versus express
bus, another way in which

00:27:13.970 --> 00:27:16.370
the MBTA segments the market.

00:27:16.370 --> 00:27:20.990
So the idea is if it's a
nicer service, you pay more.

00:27:20.990 --> 00:27:22.520
By socioeconomic status.

00:27:22.520 --> 00:27:24.710
So students might get
a discount, seniors,

00:27:24.710 --> 00:27:26.900
disabled might get a discount.

00:27:26.900 --> 00:27:29.390
We have some rules
here where seniors

00:27:29.390 --> 00:27:32.520
have to be offered
half the base fare,

00:27:32.520 --> 00:27:35.590
so that's one example of that.

00:27:35.590 --> 00:27:37.620
Some of it can be mandated
by the government.

00:27:37.620 --> 00:27:38.995
And then there's
social programs.

00:27:38.995 --> 00:27:41.000
So there's different
ways of doing that.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:43.070
It could be as part
of your participation

00:27:43.070 --> 00:27:45.800
in some social
program, it could also

00:27:45.800 --> 00:27:51.560
be a needs-based subsidy
where you essentially

00:27:51.560 --> 00:27:56.730
prove that you have financial
need and based on your need,

00:27:56.730 --> 00:27:58.370
you give some amount of subsidy.

00:27:58.370 --> 00:28:02.000
So a subsidy could be on or
off, you either have the subsidy

00:28:02.000 --> 00:28:05.520
or you don't or it could
be depending on your need,

00:28:05.520 --> 00:28:07.670
you have more subsidy
or less subsidy.

00:28:07.670 --> 00:28:10.280
And usually, it's
the simpler one.

00:28:10.280 --> 00:28:13.580
I don't actually know
of any example that

00:28:13.580 --> 00:28:16.732
is done based on
your specific case,

00:28:16.732 --> 00:28:18.440
but you could think
of doing it that way.

00:28:18.440 --> 00:28:23.890
Because if somebody is
very, very poor then

00:28:23.890 --> 00:28:26.910
they might need more
subsidy than somebody who

00:28:26.910 --> 00:28:30.124
is just below the poverty line.

00:28:30.124 --> 00:28:34.108
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] is that
because those groups tend

00:28:34.108 --> 00:28:36.754
to have less ability to
pay or what's the logic?

00:28:36.754 --> 00:28:38.920
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
That is usually the logic.

00:28:38.920 --> 00:28:40.560
So yeah.

00:28:40.560 --> 00:28:44.130
Again, it's sort of
social equity goal.

00:28:44.130 --> 00:28:50.380
So seniors and students
often can't drive, et cetera.

00:28:50.380 --> 00:28:53.460
So it's the goal of the transit
agency or the transit provider

00:28:53.460 --> 00:28:58.185
to increase mobility for
all groups of people,

00:28:58.185 --> 00:29:01.210
the way in which that
goal is satisfied.

00:29:01.210 --> 00:29:01.945
Henry.

00:29:01.945 --> 00:29:03.805
AUDIENCE: How about
programs where

00:29:03.805 --> 00:29:09.060
you can take out your income
pre-tax and [INAUDIBLE]??

00:29:09.060 --> 00:29:11.270
Is that like a social program?

00:29:11.270 --> 00:29:12.850
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: No.

00:29:12.850 --> 00:29:16.220
I do have that in
another lecture, yeah.

00:29:16.220 --> 00:29:18.260
Because that is
done for people--

00:29:18.260 --> 00:29:22.610
often, they are employee
who have a decent salary.

00:29:22.610 --> 00:29:25.000
So that's an incentive.

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:28.460
And that incentive
exists for a car as well.

00:29:28.460 --> 00:29:32.630
So that's a different strategy.

00:29:32.630 --> 00:29:34.910
Another way of segmenting
is by willingness to prepay.

00:29:34.910 --> 00:29:39.110
So in other words, are
you willing to buy a pass?

00:29:39.110 --> 00:29:41.420
So if you can commit
to a whole month,

00:29:41.420 --> 00:29:43.280
then you get some discount.

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:47.840
And this depends heavily on
what the break even point is.

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:50.830
Usually, passes-- it used
to be the case that passes

00:29:50.830 --> 00:29:52.830
had heavy discounts.

00:29:52.830 --> 00:29:59.210
So even without having a commute
two times a week for five days,

00:29:59.210 --> 00:30:01.010
you would still get a discount.

00:30:01.010 --> 00:30:05.690
Now it tends to require
sometimes between two

00:30:05.690 --> 00:30:09.050
and three trips daily to
get that break even point.

00:30:09.050 --> 00:30:11.870
Some people still decide to
go with that because it's more

00:30:11.870 --> 00:30:14.570
convenient, it's less salient.

00:30:14.570 --> 00:30:20.300
So it's another way of
discriminating or segmenting

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:22.240
the market.

00:30:22.240 --> 00:30:24.730
Any questions on
market segmentation?

00:30:24.730 --> 00:30:26.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
so speaking

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:31.439
of [INAUDIBLE],, the subsidies
given by government?

00:30:31.439 --> 00:30:32.980
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
It depends.

00:30:32.980 --> 00:30:35.020
So it could be
that the agency has

00:30:35.020 --> 00:30:37.570
a mandate they have to do this.

00:30:37.570 --> 00:30:40.630
That is often the model.

00:30:40.630 --> 00:30:42.520
From an agency's
perspective it would

00:30:42.520 --> 00:30:47.680
be much preferable to have the
subsidy come from someone else.

00:30:47.680 --> 00:30:49.540
Because then that
would allow the agency

00:30:49.540 --> 00:30:52.390
to focus on operating,
It would set fares

00:30:52.390 --> 00:30:56.140
to what it needs to cover
operational expenses.

00:30:56.140 --> 00:30:59.110
And then if it's a
social program, well,

00:30:59.110 --> 00:31:02.200
why doesn't that social
program provide the subsidy?

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:09.370
If it's disabled, maybe there's
some other government entity

00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:11.560
that can provide that subsidy.

00:31:11.560 --> 00:31:14.200
For students, why
not the schools

00:31:14.200 --> 00:31:16.240
or the Department of Education.

00:31:16.240 --> 00:31:19.420
So that's an interesting
sort of policy debate

00:31:19.420 --> 00:31:21.700
and we could talk about
it for a long time

00:31:21.700 --> 00:31:23.890
because some people are
very much against it

00:31:23.890 --> 00:31:27.300
and some people think
that's a good idea.

00:31:27.300 --> 00:31:28.110
Yeah.

00:31:28.110 --> 00:31:31.330
AUDIENCE: Also another thing
about the various groups that

00:31:31.330 --> 00:31:33.050
are entitled to
subsidies is that you

00:31:33.050 --> 00:31:36.160
have to have some mechanism
within your technology

00:31:36.160 --> 00:31:38.179
that verifies that a
person is [INAUDIBLE]..

00:31:38.179 --> 00:31:39.970
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
To prevent fraud.

00:31:39.970 --> 00:31:41.660
Yeah.

00:31:41.660 --> 00:31:45.230
So smart cards are
helpful with that

00:31:45.230 --> 00:31:51.140
because you can embed the
transit chip into a student

00:31:51.140 --> 00:31:52.360
card, for example.

00:31:52.360 --> 00:31:54.970
And that's what we
have here at MIT.

00:31:54.970 --> 00:31:55.470
OK.

00:31:55.470 --> 00:31:56.400
Fare elasticities.

00:31:56.400 --> 00:31:59.850
So they can range from -1 to 0.

00:31:59.850 --> 00:32:04.320
We know that demand of
transit is inelastic.

00:32:04.320 --> 00:32:10.860
So it means that almost always,
virtually in every case,

00:32:10.860 --> 00:32:13.020
if you raise fares, you
increase your revenue

00:32:13.020 --> 00:32:15.560
and your ridership
decreases not by too much,

00:32:15.560 --> 00:32:18.370
not by so much that your
fare revenues go down.

00:32:18.370 --> 00:32:22.680
So here are some examples
of typical elasticities.

00:32:22.680 --> 00:32:26.460
They usually are
closer to -0.3 or -0.4.

00:32:26.460 --> 00:32:32.130
For rail, it's a little
less, so -0.2, -0.15.

00:32:32.130 --> 00:32:35.010
For off-peak, it tends
to be twice as much

00:32:35.010 --> 00:32:37.830
because more trips
are discretionary.

00:32:37.830 --> 00:32:40.440
For work trips, it tends
to be much more inelastic,

00:32:40.440 --> 00:32:43.890
as we discussed, so even
half of their base one.

00:32:43.890 --> 00:32:45.600
And there's
something interesting

00:32:45.600 --> 00:32:47.560
that is maybe not as
important anymore,

00:32:47.560 --> 00:32:49.562
but I wanted to add it here.

00:32:49.562 --> 00:32:51.270
There is a higher
demand for free transit

00:32:51.270 --> 00:32:53.190
than there is for very,
very cheap transit.

00:32:53.190 --> 00:32:54.720
Even if you have
to pay, say a cent,

00:32:54.720 --> 00:33:00.570
to really get to the extreme,
the simplicity of not having

00:33:00.570 --> 00:33:03.810
to deal with paying fares, not
having to interact with a fare

00:33:03.810 --> 00:33:07.650
system, and from the marketing
point of view, it's free--

00:33:07.650 --> 00:33:11.850
you can just take it
whenever, you don't

00:33:11.850 --> 00:33:14.790
have to be ready to take it--

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:17.790
then that sort of
drives demand up.

00:33:17.790 --> 00:33:19.680
So that's an
interesting finding.

00:33:19.680 --> 00:33:21.510
A lot of agencies have
moved away from that

00:33:21.510 --> 00:33:24.150
because these are
usually smaller agencies.

00:33:24.150 --> 00:33:28.319
But of course, operational costs
increase and at some point,

00:33:28.319 --> 00:33:29.610
you need to cover them somehow.

00:33:32.210 --> 00:33:39.990
So these inelastic values
mean that raising fares

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:42.082
is an effective way of
increasing revenues.

00:33:42.082 --> 00:33:43.540
Not so much to
increase the demand,

00:33:43.540 --> 00:33:46.710
although sometimes some
aspects of fare policy

00:33:46.710 --> 00:33:48.300
are changed to
increase the amount.

00:33:48.300 --> 00:33:51.270
You know you're going to get
a small response to that.

00:33:51.270 --> 00:33:54.300
From a microeconomics
perspective,

00:33:54.300 --> 00:33:56.880
if you think about market
segmentation and running

00:33:56.880 --> 00:33:58.920
transit like a
business, then you

00:33:58.920 --> 00:34:02.760
would want to charge
more for longer trips;

00:34:02.760 --> 00:34:05.640
trips in more convenient,
reliable, comfortable,

00:34:05.640 --> 00:34:09.420
and frequent modes; peak
period trips; trips where

00:34:09.420 --> 00:34:12.750
other modes are inconvenient
or costly, therefore this

00:34:12.750 --> 00:34:15.030
is the best option and why
not charge more for it;

00:34:15.030 --> 00:34:17.250
and trips subsidized
by third parties

00:34:17.250 --> 00:34:20.639
because then you could
capture some of the increased

00:34:20.639 --> 00:34:22.590
fare from an outside source.

00:34:22.590 --> 00:34:23.159
All right.

00:34:23.159 --> 00:34:27.060
So of course, not
everybody would

00:34:27.060 --> 00:34:29.730
agree that this is what
agencies should do.

00:34:29.730 --> 00:34:31.230
But if you are
thinking of running

00:34:31.230 --> 00:34:34.170
an agency as a business, this
is exactly what you want.

00:34:34.170 --> 00:34:37.530
If you have more willingness
to pay for whatever reason,

00:34:37.530 --> 00:34:39.139
your fare is higher.

00:34:39.139 --> 00:34:41.760
And that means that
fare revenues go up

00:34:41.760 --> 00:34:43.969
and your fare recovery
ratio goes up.

00:34:43.969 --> 00:34:46.949
And that means you can
operate more service

00:34:46.949 --> 00:34:48.780
or you can operate more
reliably or you can

00:34:48.780 --> 00:34:50.591
get nicer vehicles, et cetera.

00:34:50.591 --> 00:34:51.090
All right.

00:34:53.880 --> 00:34:55.900
So transfer pricing and policy.

00:34:55.900 --> 00:34:58.320
Another issue,
some agencies don't

00:34:58.320 --> 00:35:02.670
have any sort of
integration between rides

00:35:02.670 --> 00:35:05.790
so every time you board a
vehicle, you pay a full fare

00:35:05.790 --> 00:35:07.710
and there's no free transfer.

00:35:07.710 --> 00:35:10.470
Some agencies have a
reduced price transfer

00:35:10.470 --> 00:35:11.880
or a free transfer.

00:35:11.880 --> 00:35:14.950
And free transfers can be
done in different ways.

00:35:14.950 --> 00:35:17.250
One of the most
common ways is to have

00:35:17.250 --> 00:35:19.590
a time-based free transfer.

00:35:19.590 --> 00:35:23.850
So you tap and you
get, say, an hour

00:35:23.850 --> 00:35:29.920
or two hours of free transit
starting from that point.

00:35:29.920 --> 00:35:33.270
So if you transfer,
you'll presumably

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:36.450
be in this two-hour window
and the next time you tap,

00:35:36.450 --> 00:35:38.490
it'll be a free transfer.

00:35:38.490 --> 00:35:42.390
Here in the MBTA, the price
is higher for rail and bus.

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:45.390
So if you transfer from bus to
rail, you pay the difference.

00:35:45.390 --> 00:35:49.440
If you transfer from rail
to bus, both are free.

00:35:49.440 --> 00:35:52.110
Interestingly, with
this time-based rule,

00:35:52.110 --> 00:35:55.360
you can often do something
very quickly and return

00:35:55.360 --> 00:35:57.510
and these are actually
two different trips

00:35:57.510 --> 00:36:02.000
and you would still
get a free return trip

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:03.640
and it's not a transfer.

00:36:03.640 --> 00:36:05.460
So with more complex
fare rules, you

00:36:05.460 --> 00:36:09.270
could say you should get free
transfers within this window,

00:36:09.270 --> 00:36:11.340
but not if you are
on the same bus route

00:36:11.340 --> 00:36:14.220
or if you are tapping into
the same station or things

00:36:14.220 --> 00:36:15.150
like this.

00:36:15.150 --> 00:36:17.880
You could think
of the rules used

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:21.880
for transfer insurance when we
discussed all the [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:21.880 --> 00:36:23.940
These are not fare transfers.

00:36:23.940 --> 00:36:26.260
Those were sort of a
logical trip transfers

00:36:26.260 --> 00:36:27.900
and you could apply those rules.

00:36:27.900 --> 00:36:29.640
You could put them
into a fare engine

00:36:29.640 --> 00:36:35.160
and not give free transfers
when it's not a transfer.

00:36:35.160 --> 00:36:35.670
OK.

00:36:35.670 --> 00:36:37.950
Pay-as-you-go,
passes, and capping.

00:36:37.950 --> 00:36:38.450
OK.

00:36:38.450 --> 00:36:40.340
One question before we--

00:36:40.340 --> 00:36:41.100
Daniel.

00:36:41.100 --> 00:36:43.250
Yeah.

00:36:43.250 --> 00:36:44.770
AUDIENCE: Is there--
how do agencies

00:36:44.770 --> 00:36:48.796
determine if it's unlimited free
transfers within the same trip

00:36:48.796 --> 00:36:52.030
or [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:52.030 --> 00:36:57.088
Because [INAUDIBLE] bus,
rail, bus [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:57.088 --> 00:36:58.550
have to [INAUDIBLE].

00:36:58.550 --> 00:36:59.000
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
You usually

00:36:59.000 --> 00:37:01.370
don't have to because they
set the window wide enough

00:37:01.370 --> 00:37:05.600
so that you can get your
whole three-four trip done

00:37:05.600 --> 00:37:07.121
in that two-hour window.

00:37:07.121 --> 00:37:09.942
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] trips and
I've been charged [INAUDIBLE]..

00:37:09.942 --> 00:37:11.150
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Oh.

00:37:11.150 --> 00:37:14.270
In theory, I think you could
go to customer service and say,

00:37:14.270 --> 00:37:15.410
this was a transfer.

00:37:15.410 --> 00:37:17.420
Your policy is free transfers.

00:37:17.420 --> 00:37:21.880
You need to refund me.

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:22.380
Yeah.

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:28.230
I don't know the
details of it, but I

00:37:28.230 --> 00:37:30.105
imagine that's the case,
that you could argue

00:37:30.105 --> 00:37:31.290
that you deserve a refund.

00:37:31.290 --> 00:37:33.266
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] paid
fare policy [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:33.266 --> 00:37:34.200
reach your [INAUDIBLE].

00:37:34.200 --> 00:37:35.408
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: OK.

00:37:35.408 --> 00:37:37.260
I haven't, clearly.

00:37:37.260 --> 00:37:39.630
It would probably be very
interesting, actually.

00:37:39.630 --> 00:37:42.196
Any other questions
on transfers?

00:37:42.196 --> 00:37:44.070
Transfers are more of
an issue when there are

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:46.137
multiple operators in a region.

00:37:46.137 --> 00:37:47.970
And we'll talk a little
bit more about that.

00:37:47.970 --> 00:37:53.890
If it's one operator, that's
sort of less controversial.

00:37:53.890 --> 00:37:54.510
OK.

00:37:54.510 --> 00:37:56.850
So pay-as-you-go
passes and capping.

00:37:56.850 --> 00:38:02.580
So pay-as-you-go is the simplest
way of paying for trips.

00:38:02.580 --> 00:38:05.190
You can do that with cash or
with tickets or smart cards

00:38:05.190 --> 00:38:06.670
that have a balance.

00:38:06.670 --> 00:38:09.210
So you load up some
value onto the card

00:38:09.210 --> 00:38:14.080
and every time you interact
with a fare box or fare gate,

00:38:14.080 --> 00:38:18.480
some amount of that balance
is deducted from the card.

00:38:18.480 --> 00:38:20.407
That's pretty clear, hopefully.

00:38:20.407 --> 00:38:21.240
Then there's passes.

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:23.850
So the idea of a pass is
that you sort of prepay

00:38:23.850 --> 00:38:28.650
for three days, for a
week, sometimes for a day,

00:38:28.650 --> 00:38:30.060
sometimes for a month.

00:38:30.060 --> 00:38:35.610
And it's a fixed price so you
ride with zero marginal costs

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:37.330
after paying that fixed price.

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:40.230
If you ride frequently
enough, then you break even

00:38:40.230 --> 00:38:42.790
and anything beyond
that is a free ride.

00:38:42.790 --> 00:38:48.360
So it's interesting to note that
because passes are convenient,

00:38:48.360 --> 00:38:51.630
some fare revenue is
derived from past sales

00:38:51.630 --> 00:38:54.210
for people that
don't break even.

00:38:54.210 --> 00:38:55.840
That could happen
for several reasons.

00:38:55.840 --> 00:38:57.780
One of them might be
it's more convenient

00:38:57.780 --> 00:39:00.690
and I'm not going to figure
out every month if I'm

00:39:00.690 --> 00:39:03.420
going to be having the
pass or not the pass.

00:39:03.420 --> 00:39:06.510
It could also be that some
people receive a subsidy

00:39:06.510 --> 00:39:09.660
from somewhere and
what they spend

00:39:09.660 --> 00:39:12.126
on the pass is lower
than the pass value.

00:39:12.126 --> 00:39:14.250
And so for them, the real
break even point is lower

00:39:14.250 --> 00:39:17.580
and you may not necessarily
be considering that when

00:39:17.580 --> 00:39:19.681
you do this break even
point calculation.

00:39:22.390 --> 00:39:27.072
So in some cases, going
back to transfers, agencies

00:39:27.072 --> 00:39:28.530
that don't have
free transfers, you

00:39:28.530 --> 00:39:30.870
can get them indirectly
through a pass.

00:39:30.870 --> 00:39:33.660
Because they might
say, well, you

00:39:33.660 --> 00:39:36.480
break even at 10 rides
per week so that's

00:39:36.480 --> 00:39:41.400
your five weekdays times
two of going and returning.

00:39:41.400 --> 00:39:44.880
And if you have no
free transfers policy

00:39:44.880 --> 00:39:47.610
but your trip
requires one transfer,

00:39:47.610 --> 00:39:50.430
then you're going to very
quickly reach that limit

00:39:50.430 --> 00:39:52.420
and you're going to
ride free after that.

00:39:52.420 --> 00:39:56.590
So in practice, that would
be a free transfer policy,

00:39:56.590 --> 00:39:58.770
although not directly.

00:39:58.770 --> 00:40:01.430
So passes increase
convenience, we know that.

00:40:01.430 --> 00:40:03.290
The reduce saliency
so you're not

00:40:03.290 --> 00:40:05.720
thinking about how much money
you're paying every time

00:40:05.720 --> 00:40:07.820
because it's more convenient.

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:11.240
They can be subsidized by
employers, by universities,

00:40:11.240 --> 00:40:11.990
by governments.

00:40:11.990 --> 00:40:14.610
So here we talk about
the pre-tax benefit

00:40:14.610 --> 00:40:16.310
that Henry brought up.

00:40:16.310 --> 00:40:18.440
And then there are
social programs,

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:21.890
like access to jobs
programs, that give

00:40:21.890 --> 00:40:24.860
passes subsidized or
sometimes even free

00:40:24.860 --> 00:40:29.660
for people that are
economically disadvantaged.

00:40:29.660 --> 00:40:31.340
Questions on passes?

00:40:31.340 --> 00:40:33.091
I think we're all
familiar with passes.

00:40:33.091 --> 00:40:33.590
OK.

00:40:33.590 --> 00:40:36.950
So capping is less common,
it's a newer thing.

00:40:36.950 --> 00:40:38.300
It's more common in Europe.

00:40:38.300 --> 00:40:41.400
London has it, Germany has it
in many places, the Netherlands.

00:40:41.400 --> 00:40:47.000
So the idea is that when
you have a complex fare

00:40:47.000 --> 00:40:51.980
structure where the prices
are difficult to figure out,

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:56.030
then the agency says, don't
worry about calculating which

00:40:56.030 --> 00:40:58.910
fare products you need
to buy; we'll do the math

00:40:58.910 --> 00:41:01.140
and give you the best price.

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:03.050
So that's called
best price guarantee.

00:41:03.050 --> 00:41:05.480
And the idea is that
instead of committing

00:41:05.480 --> 00:41:08.390
to getting a pass
or not a pass, you

00:41:08.390 --> 00:41:12.350
pay as you go but when you
reach a certain daily limit,

00:41:12.350 --> 00:41:14.550
no more is charged
during that day.

00:41:14.550 --> 00:41:15.950
So you can keep riding.

00:41:15.950 --> 00:41:17.670
And that doesn't stop there.

00:41:17.670 --> 00:41:20.450
So the card keeps
counting the trips

00:41:20.450 --> 00:41:23.060
in one week, the
trips in one month.

00:41:23.060 --> 00:41:25.180
And so you might
have multiple caps

00:41:25.180 --> 00:41:29.080
and you might reach
different caps on one session

00:41:29.080 --> 00:41:31.280
sort of with one card.

00:41:31.280 --> 00:41:34.220
So essentially,
you end up getting

00:41:34.220 --> 00:41:38.570
the equivalent of a pass if it
was worth it and not otherwise.

00:41:38.570 --> 00:41:41.300
Obviously, that means
agencies lose some revenue

00:41:41.300 --> 00:41:44.640
from people who didn't
make the right decision,

00:41:44.640 --> 00:41:50.030
but it's one way of having a
complex fare structure that

00:41:50.030 --> 00:41:52.220
heavily segments the
market and therefore does

00:41:52.220 --> 00:41:53.870
obtain more fare revenues.

00:41:53.870 --> 00:41:59.930
And it allows for simple
communication with people

00:41:59.930 --> 00:42:02.720
by saying, don't worry about
it; we know it's complicated,

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:04.640
but we'll figure it out for you.

00:42:04.640 --> 00:42:08.250
That's one argument.

00:42:08.250 --> 00:42:11.010
In London, one of the reasons
capping was introduced

00:42:11.010 --> 00:42:15.030
was with the movement to
contactless bank cards.

00:42:15.030 --> 00:42:18.350
So essentially, you can pay
with your Visa or MasterCard.

00:42:18.350 --> 00:42:21.570
You can have it on your phone,
Apple Pay or Android Pay,

00:42:21.570 --> 00:42:24.550
you tap, it works.

00:42:24.550 --> 00:42:28.830
So obviously, a
normal Visa might not

00:42:28.830 --> 00:42:32.070
have the logic inside
the card's computer

00:42:32.070 --> 00:42:35.410
to hold a pass or
anything like that

00:42:35.410 --> 00:42:37.260
so the card becomes a token.

00:42:37.260 --> 00:42:41.610
One way of dealing with
that is to say, it's capped.

00:42:41.610 --> 00:42:43.740
We'll keep track of
your usage for the month

00:42:43.740 --> 00:42:45.660
and when you reach
the monthly cap,

00:42:45.660 --> 00:42:47.820
we'll stop charging you for it.

00:42:47.820 --> 00:42:52.650
So it simplifies the move to or
towards contactless bank card

00:42:52.650 --> 00:42:53.770
usage.

00:42:53.770 --> 00:42:55.210
And we'll talk more about that.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:55.490
Yeah.

00:42:55.490 --> 00:42:57.239
AUDIENCE: So since
London introduced this,

00:42:57.239 --> 00:43:00.040
have they seen a drop in the
number of pass purchases?

00:43:00.040 --> 00:43:01.290
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yes.

00:43:01.290 --> 00:43:03.270
Well, they've seen
an increase in--

00:43:03.270 --> 00:43:06.270
the penetration for
contactless bank card use

00:43:06.270 --> 00:43:07.830
has been increasing steadily.

00:43:07.830 --> 00:43:12.030
And if you go to London,
my last experience there

00:43:12.030 --> 00:43:16.500
was on the train ride
between the airport

00:43:16.500 --> 00:43:20.670
and the center of London, I
heard several people talking

00:43:20.670 --> 00:43:22.050
about how convenient it was.

00:43:22.050 --> 00:43:24.960
So people are
excited about this.

00:43:24.960 --> 00:43:27.150
And it's great for
a city like London

00:43:27.150 --> 00:43:28.640
that has a lot of
people that are

00:43:28.640 --> 00:43:31.950
occasional users, a lot of
business travelers being

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:34.290
able to not have
to think about it

00:43:34.290 --> 00:43:36.350
and just pay with a credit card.

00:43:36.350 --> 00:43:38.760
It really helps.

00:43:38.760 --> 00:43:40.230
And it has several
other benefits.

00:43:40.230 --> 00:43:43.129
I'll discuss them more in detail
when we get to smart cards.

00:43:43.129 --> 00:43:44.670
AUDIENCE: If you
say that it's capped

00:43:44.670 --> 00:43:48.080
and you said that there's
a trend away from passes,

00:43:48.080 --> 00:43:49.650
people are not buying passes.

00:43:49.650 --> 00:43:51.650
But isn't that essentially
saying that actually,

00:43:51.650 --> 00:43:54.120
no; people are buying
more passes than ever.

00:43:54.120 --> 00:43:56.900
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Well,
it's capping so it's not--

00:43:56.900 --> 00:43:58.524
AUDIENCE: It's
capping, but it comes--

00:43:58.524 --> 00:44:00.690
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
It's equivalent to a pass.

00:44:00.690 --> 00:44:02.340
The math works out
so that it a pass,

00:44:02.340 --> 00:44:04.970
but you're not selling
a monthly pass.

00:44:04.970 --> 00:44:05.760
Yeah.

00:44:05.760 --> 00:44:07.650
It's not a pass.

00:44:07.650 --> 00:44:08.767
You're paying each ride.

00:44:08.767 --> 00:44:09.840
AUDIENCE: --acts
like a [INAUDIBLE]..

00:44:09.840 --> 00:44:10.640
It induces [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:10.640 --> 00:44:11.264
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:44:11.264 --> 00:44:14.340
But I think if you go to
London every couple of months

00:44:14.340 --> 00:44:16.330
and you can just
show up in London

00:44:16.330 --> 00:44:18.704
and you don't have to fill up
an Oyster card or anything.

00:44:18.704 --> 00:44:21.525
You can tap your card and use
it like you normally would.

00:44:21.525 --> 00:44:24.060
If you ride too much in a
day, they cap it as well,

00:44:24.060 --> 00:44:26.430
which is something they
don't do on a monthly pass.

00:44:26.430 --> 00:44:27.721
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:44:29.430 --> 00:44:29.970
OK.

00:44:29.970 --> 00:44:32.280
We'll discuss more on the
contactless bank cards.

00:44:32.280 --> 00:44:35.040
This is a very interesting
trend that we're seeing.

00:44:35.040 --> 00:44:37.650
So fare policy demand analysis,
we talked a little bit

00:44:37.650 --> 00:44:40.080
about this on
ridership forecasting.

00:44:40.080 --> 00:44:42.930
Just a little recap, the
traditional four-step modeling

00:44:42.930 --> 00:44:44.580
process is not
usually appropriate.

00:44:44.580 --> 00:44:48.270
And that's because A, it has
insufficient spatiotemporal

00:44:48.270 --> 00:44:52.140
resolution and B, the planning
horizon for a fare hike

00:44:52.140 --> 00:44:55.500
is kind of short- to
medium-term so you're not

00:44:55.500 --> 00:45:00.120
thinking about land use changes
that will generate new trips.

00:45:00.120 --> 00:45:03.300
So therefore, total amount
is, we can assume, fixed.

00:45:03.300 --> 00:45:05.970
And what you want to play
with is the modal split

00:45:05.970 --> 00:45:10.680
and the assignment
to specific trips.

00:45:10.680 --> 00:45:12.930
The other thing is that these
four-step models usually

00:45:12.930 --> 00:45:15.810
don't have all the details of
all the fare products in them.

00:45:15.810 --> 00:45:17.850
And for an agency,
it's important to know

00:45:17.850 --> 00:45:20.010
what people will do
about getting a pass

00:45:20.010 --> 00:45:21.600
or paying as they go.

00:45:21.600 --> 00:45:26.040
So usually, fare elasticity
analysis is simple;

00:45:26.040 --> 00:45:29.520
in reality, a passenger is
considering multiple things

00:45:29.520 --> 00:45:30.400
at the same time.

00:45:30.400 --> 00:45:33.256
So which mode are
they going to take,

00:45:33.256 --> 00:45:35.130
are they going to drive
their car or are they

00:45:35.130 --> 00:45:39.430
going to take transit, are
they going to take bus or rail?

00:45:39.430 --> 00:45:41.610
Fare products, are they
going to go for the pass

00:45:41.610 --> 00:45:43.109
or are they going
to pay as they go?

00:45:43.109 --> 00:45:45.610
And maybe there are
multiple passes, which one?

00:45:45.610 --> 00:45:48.630
And then costs, not
just in absolute terms.

00:45:48.630 --> 00:45:50.940
So usually,
elasticity only looks

00:45:50.940 --> 00:45:54.760
at the percentage increase
in fares for this mode.

00:45:54.760 --> 00:45:58.350
But what if car costs have
gone up by more than that.

00:45:58.350 --> 00:46:01.570
So really, it's relative
to your alternatives

00:46:01.570 --> 00:46:03.660
and each person might
have a different choice.

00:46:03.660 --> 00:46:07.820
For some people, transit might
be the only mode of choice

00:46:07.820 --> 00:46:10.080
[INAUDIBLE] the only
mode in the choice set

00:46:10.080 --> 00:46:11.700
because they don't own a car.

00:46:11.700 --> 00:46:15.610
For others, there may
be multiple options.

00:46:15.610 --> 00:46:18.741
So the other aspect of it
is that exogenous factors

00:46:18.741 --> 00:46:21.240
influence demand response and
they're not usually controlled

00:46:21.240 --> 00:46:21.739
for.

00:46:21.739 --> 00:46:24.420
So fuel prices, employment,
residential development,

00:46:24.420 --> 00:46:27.210
tax policy,
sociodemographics, new modes--

00:46:27.210 --> 00:46:30.230
the introduction of
TNCs like Uber and Lyft

00:46:30.230 --> 00:46:36.720
and other companies have
potentially affected ridership,

00:46:36.720 --> 00:46:37.730
we think they have.

00:46:37.730 --> 00:46:40.250
And most of these
elasticity models

00:46:40.250 --> 00:46:43.610
don't really sort
of control for that

00:46:43.610 --> 00:46:46.460
to get the real fare
elasticity, and that

00:46:46.460 --> 00:46:51.740
would be what you would want
to do, an accurate model.

00:46:51.740 --> 00:46:52.240
OK.

00:46:52.240 --> 00:46:53.740
Communication of fare policy.

00:46:53.740 --> 00:46:56.470
So obviously, to the public
it needs to be communicated.

00:46:56.470 --> 00:46:57.970
You can do that on
your website, you

00:46:57.970 --> 00:47:00.890
can have near fare vending
machines there's usually you

00:47:00.890 --> 00:47:03.060
know an explanation
of the prices,

00:47:03.060 --> 00:47:05.179
you have a customer
service booths.

00:47:05.179 --> 00:47:06.970
If there's going to be
a fare change, again

00:47:06.970 --> 00:47:09.386
you post things on the website;
there's flyers and posters

00:47:09.386 --> 00:47:11.740
everywhere; public
hearings, of course,

00:47:11.740 --> 00:47:17.080
to sort of hear complaints
and defend the hike.

00:47:17.080 --> 00:47:20.290
And I wanted to add one sort
of third emerging but very

00:47:20.290 --> 00:47:25.110
important aspect that
we haven't figured out,

00:47:25.110 --> 00:47:28.300
and it's via APIs or standard
feeds for trip planners.

00:47:28.300 --> 00:47:32.020
So if you have an app or if you
use Google Maps to get transit

00:47:32.020 --> 00:47:34.990
directions and you want it to
calculate what your fare will

00:47:34.990 --> 00:47:38.290
be, unless the agency has
a simple fare structure,

00:47:38.290 --> 00:47:39.082
that can't be done.

00:47:39.082 --> 00:47:41.248
Even for agencies that have
a simple fare structure,

00:47:41.248 --> 00:47:43.240
most of them don't
provide the two files

00:47:43.240 --> 00:47:46.600
in GTFS that allow that
calculation to happen.

00:47:46.600 --> 00:47:49.410
And for agencies like London
that have a capping scheme,

00:47:49.410 --> 00:47:51.820
the GTFS specification
does not provide the means

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:56.564
by which to input the fare
rules that would accurately

00:47:56.564 --> 00:47:57.730
calculate the person's fare.

00:47:57.730 --> 00:47:59.229
Because you would
need to keep track

00:47:59.229 --> 00:48:04.410
of how much they've taken
service over a week,

00:48:04.410 --> 00:48:05.560
over a day, et cetera.

00:48:05.560 --> 00:48:08.680
So that we haven't figured out.

00:48:08.680 --> 00:48:11.500
Third party apps
like the transit app

00:48:11.500 --> 00:48:14.170
would love to be able
to calculate fares

00:48:14.170 --> 00:48:15.541
accurately and display them.

00:48:15.541 --> 00:48:17.290
Because they can do
that for Uber and they

00:48:17.290 --> 00:48:22.665
can do that for other modes,
so why not for transit as well?

00:48:22.665 --> 00:48:24.790
And although they would
prefer to do that in-house,

00:48:24.790 --> 00:48:28.330
one alternative to
that is to define

00:48:28.330 --> 00:48:30.550
some sort of standard
API where it's

00:48:30.550 --> 00:48:34.720
up to the agency to
calculate what that would be.

00:48:34.720 --> 00:48:37.150
But you make an API
call and you say,

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:39.340
this is the hypothetical
trip that I'm planning.

00:48:39.340 --> 00:48:43.810
Give me how much [INAUDIBLE]
and the agency would respond.

00:48:43.810 --> 00:48:47.170
But for performance
reasons I think

00:48:47.170 --> 00:48:48.700
the transit app
would prefer to be

00:48:48.700 --> 00:48:50.146
able to do that
with their servers

00:48:50.146 --> 00:48:51.520
so that there's
a quick response.

00:48:54.310 --> 00:48:57.250
Partnerships, another
sort of emerging trend.

00:48:57.250 --> 00:48:59.270
So employer partnerships
is one example.

00:48:59.270 --> 00:49:01.080
I'll give you the
example of MIT, actually.

00:49:01.080 --> 00:49:03.910
MIT has something
called AccessMyCommute.

00:49:03.910 --> 00:49:06.010
Our lab was actually
involved in that.

00:49:06.010 --> 00:49:10.360
So every MIT student
or employee badge

00:49:10.360 --> 00:49:13.060
has a Charlie chip
embedded inside.

00:49:13.060 --> 00:49:15.610
You can look at the back
and it says, Charlie inside.

00:49:15.610 --> 00:49:20.560
And to employees, it's marketed
as an unlimited use pass.

00:49:20.560 --> 00:49:23.560
So I can use my MIT
ID and ride the MBTA.

00:49:27.020 --> 00:49:30.220
MIT gets billed on a
pay-as-you-go basis.

00:49:30.220 --> 00:49:34.780
So the reason that
was the agreement

00:49:34.780 --> 00:49:38.380
is that a lot of people
don't use transit enough

00:49:38.380 --> 00:49:40.280
to justify the value of a pass.

00:49:40.280 --> 00:49:43.960
So there was no
way that MIT would

00:49:43.960 --> 00:49:47.080
agree to pay a pass
for every employee.

00:49:47.080 --> 00:49:49.690
And it's in the interest
of MIT to foment,

00:49:49.690 --> 00:49:53.500
to encourage ridership,
so to decrease saliency,

00:49:53.500 --> 00:49:56.560
in this case to the
extreme by making it free.

00:49:56.560 --> 00:50:01.950
So one way of doing that is to
say, market it as a free pass.

00:50:01.950 --> 00:50:07.770
There is a mix of people that
had passes and people that

00:50:07.770 --> 00:50:09.546
ride less often.

00:50:09.546 --> 00:50:10.920
AUDIENCE: Could
MIT reach a point

00:50:10.920 --> 00:50:13.570
where it might actually
want everyone to the pass

00:50:13.570 --> 00:50:16.780
without the [INAUDIBLE]
employees knowing it

00:50:16.780 --> 00:50:17.280
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:17.280 --> 00:50:17.490
GABRIEL
SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: I don't

00:50:17.490 --> 00:50:19.780
think so because many,
many employees-- yeah,

00:50:19.780 --> 00:50:20.880
it's not close.

00:50:20.880 --> 00:50:26.610
And some people ride
a lot more so MIT

00:50:26.610 --> 00:50:30.150
in some ways for some
employees is paying more

00:50:30.150 --> 00:50:32.070
because they're paying by ride.

00:50:32.070 --> 00:50:34.560
But many people that
have a subsidized pass

00:50:34.560 --> 00:50:38.530
because their break even
point is so much lower

00:50:38.530 --> 00:50:39.930
don't really break even.

00:50:39.930 --> 00:50:42.570
And so it works out to--

00:50:42.570 --> 00:50:45.360
AUDIENCE: The next project
that project might do

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:47.940
is to find a way
to predict based

00:50:47.940 --> 00:50:51.282
on the employee [INAUDIBLE]
this information

00:50:51.282 --> 00:50:53.490
and they make a prediction
for what he's going to do.

00:50:53.490 --> 00:50:55.460
And you might save MIT
a fair amount of money.

00:50:55.460 --> 00:50:56.751
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:50:56.751 --> 00:50:58.800
Well, one of the
reasons MIT decided

00:50:58.800 --> 00:51:00.870
to do this is because
parking is very expensive,

00:51:00.870 --> 00:51:03.720
real state is very
expensive-- very expensive.

00:51:03.720 --> 00:51:06.840
And that's, of course,
not true everywhere.

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:08.070
It's not true in most places.

00:51:08.070 --> 00:51:11.130
Most places have free
parking, plenty of land.

00:51:11.130 --> 00:51:14.370
But in a place that has high
density, building new parking

00:51:14.370 --> 00:51:17.190
is very expensive and you
could use that real state

00:51:17.190 --> 00:51:18.220
for something else.

00:51:18.220 --> 00:51:20.850
In fact, MIT has taken a
parking down near Sloan

00:51:20.850 --> 00:51:22.730
and is making a
new building there.

00:51:22.730 --> 00:51:26.970
So it costs less to
provide transit to people

00:51:26.970 --> 00:51:28.860
and to encourage
people to take transit

00:51:28.860 --> 00:51:31.350
than to build new parking
and maintain parking.

00:51:34.170 --> 00:51:35.530
Here's another example.

00:51:35.530 --> 00:51:39.000
So the Chicago
Transit Authority has

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:41.280
partnerships with other
transportation providers.

00:51:41.280 --> 00:51:44.190
And they do that by providing--

00:51:44.190 --> 00:51:47.550
there are some passes and
some fare products that

00:51:47.550 --> 00:51:50.619
allow riding in PACE, which
is the original bus provider;

00:51:50.619 --> 00:51:52.410
Metra, which is the
commuter rail provider;

00:51:52.410 --> 00:51:55.470
and Divvy, which
is the bike share.

00:51:55.470 --> 00:51:59.460
So you can buy things that--

00:51:59.460 --> 00:52:02.490
there are some partnerships that
allow some integration here.

00:52:02.490 --> 00:52:05.320
And there is a trend towards
mobility as a service.

00:52:05.320 --> 00:52:08.030
So the idea of
mobility as a service

00:52:08.030 --> 00:52:10.170
is that you make a monthly
payment for a bundle

00:52:10.170 --> 00:52:12.850
of transportation options.

00:52:12.850 --> 00:52:13.990
Here's an example.

00:52:13.990 --> 00:52:18.000
You could have unlimited transit
pass five bike rides and five

00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:18.840
TNC rides.

00:52:21.660 --> 00:52:24.840
So you provide this bundle.

00:52:24.840 --> 00:52:28.020
The person is purchasing
my transportation from home

00:52:28.020 --> 00:52:30.860
to work and back on a
combination of both.

00:52:30.860 --> 00:52:34.430
So if it's today it's
inconvenient to take transit,

00:52:34.430 --> 00:52:39.960
that day I will use the
bike share or the TNC.

00:52:39.960 --> 00:52:43.410
The word is out on whether
this will work or not.

00:52:43.410 --> 00:52:45.720
Many agencies are
interested; most of them

00:52:45.720 --> 00:52:47.250
don't want to talk about it.

00:52:47.250 --> 00:52:51.392
And we'll see what
happens as time goes by.

