00:53:32.000 --> 00:53:36.091
So many other factors play in.

00:53:36.091 --> 00:53:36.590
OK.

00:53:36.590 --> 00:53:38.260
Fare control.

00:53:38.260 --> 00:53:40.210
Tap in, you know what that is.

00:53:40.210 --> 00:53:42.650
You interact with a
fare box or fare gate

00:53:42.650 --> 00:53:45.450
only when you're entering
the system or vehicle.

00:53:45.450 --> 00:53:48.980
Tap in and tap out, you do
that when you enter and exit.

00:53:48.980 --> 00:53:54.650
Usually, tap in and tap out
is for systems that have zones

00:53:54.650 --> 00:53:57.110
and you tap out so
that we know if you've

00:53:57.110 --> 00:53:59.210
traveled multiple zones
or not and therefore, we

00:53:59.210 --> 00:54:01.790
know how much to charge you
because of the segmentation

00:54:01.790 --> 00:54:04.550
by geography.

00:54:04.550 --> 00:54:08.570
It also happens when there
are multiple agencies sharing

00:54:08.570 --> 00:54:09.660
the revenue.

00:54:09.660 --> 00:54:18.800
So intercity bus in some cities,
if a person takes a bus route

00:54:18.800 --> 00:54:22.400
within a city, then that
revenue would go to that city.

00:54:22.400 --> 00:54:25.400
If the person travels
across cities,

00:54:25.400 --> 00:54:27.650
then the revenue would
be shared across cities.

00:54:27.650 --> 00:54:31.070
So that's one way you
might want to do this.

00:54:31.070 --> 00:54:33.849
I know that it does exist
in some places for bus

00:54:33.849 --> 00:54:35.390
where you have to
tap in and tap out,

00:54:35.390 --> 00:54:38.940
although it's much less
common for bus than for rail.

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:40.218
Henry.

00:54:40.218 --> 00:54:45.670
AUDIENCE: If the tap system
introduces a day pass,

00:54:45.670 --> 00:54:49.269
for example, where
[INAUDIBLE] go to multiple--

00:54:49.269 --> 00:54:50.560
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:54:50.560 --> 00:54:51.250
Yeah.

00:54:51.250 --> 00:54:51.720
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:54:51.720 --> 00:54:53.011
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

00:54:53.011 --> 00:54:55.031
AUDIENCE: Then would
they just [INAUDIBLE]..

00:54:55.031 --> 00:54:57.280
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: I
don't know how they do it.

00:54:57.280 --> 00:54:59.530
Funding formulas
are a huge debate.

00:54:59.530 --> 00:55:04.060
And as an engineer, I would
propose to look at their OD

00:55:04.060 --> 00:55:09.250
and figure out the most fair
way of allocating that revenue.

00:55:09.250 --> 00:55:13.747
But how would they actually
do it is probably simpler.

00:55:13.747 --> 00:55:15.330
Another thing about
tap in and tap out

00:55:15.330 --> 00:55:18.380
is that you may require
internal vending machines.

00:55:18.380 --> 00:55:20.970
It may increase
your capital costs.

00:55:20.970 --> 00:55:21.690
Why is that?

00:55:21.690 --> 00:55:24.660
Because you have multiple costs.

00:55:24.660 --> 00:55:27.260
The price of your ride
depends on how far you ride

00:55:27.260 --> 00:55:28.590
and if you cross zones or not.

00:55:28.590 --> 00:55:30.131
So you might have
just enough balance

00:55:30.131 --> 00:55:33.900
to enter, not enough to exit
if you cross multiple zones.

00:55:33.900 --> 00:55:37.170
So you might have
to top up the card

00:55:37.170 --> 00:55:38.754
before being allowed to exit.

00:55:38.754 --> 00:55:40.170
That means you
need a fare vending

00:55:40.170 --> 00:55:45.165
machine that a person
can use to top up

00:55:45.165 --> 00:55:47.250
if they don't have a pass.

00:55:47.250 --> 00:55:50.070
It means that you might
need a station attendant

00:55:50.070 --> 00:55:51.030
to deal with somebody.

00:55:51.030 --> 00:55:53.640
If the fare vending
machine is not working

00:55:53.640 --> 00:55:56.460
or my bank card is not
working and is being rejected,

00:55:56.460 --> 00:55:59.910
I need to get out
of the station.

00:55:59.910 --> 00:56:00.690
I'm trapped.

00:56:00.690 --> 00:56:02.430
So what do I do?

00:56:02.430 --> 00:56:05.400
So it can increase
costs in that way.

00:56:05.400 --> 00:56:06.570
You had a comment?

00:56:06.570 --> 00:56:07.570
OK.

00:56:07.570 --> 00:56:08.831
No.

00:56:08.831 --> 00:56:09.330
Right.

00:56:09.330 --> 00:56:12.030
So that's one potential issue.

00:56:12.030 --> 00:56:15.850
Something that some agencies do
is allowing a negative balance.

00:56:15.850 --> 00:56:18.420
So when we are
softening the blows

00:56:18.420 --> 00:56:22.590
to allow when you tap
out to go below zero.

00:56:22.590 --> 00:56:28.800
Next time you fill up the card,
you top up, if you put in $20

00:56:28.800 --> 00:56:31.540
and you had a $1 deficit,
your balance is now $19.

00:56:34.470 --> 00:56:37.920
You can't do that if cards
are [INAUDIBLE] because people

00:56:37.920 --> 00:56:40.590
will then toss the
card and get a new one.

00:56:40.590 --> 00:56:43.410
So you make people buy the.

00:56:43.410 --> 00:56:48.160
The cards are maybe $10 and
a $5 balance or something.

00:56:48.160 --> 00:56:51.810
So there's a disincentive
to tossing the card

00:56:51.810 --> 00:56:54.180
and getting a new one.

00:56:54.180 --> 00:56:56.280
And by the way, smart
cards cost money.

00:56:56.280 --> 00:56:58.350
They're not that cheap.

00:56:58.350 --> 00:57:01.920
Some agencies have paid $10
per card for their card.

00:57:05.080 --> 00:57:07.410
Proof of payments, we
sort of discussed that.

00:57:07.410 --> 00:57:10.840
You buy a ticket.

00:57:10.840 --> 00:57:12.840
It might be OD, it
might be flat fare.

00:57:12.840 --> 00:57:15.480
It doesn't matter, you buy
the ticket that you need.

00:57:15.480 --> 00:57:18.990
And then when you board,
there's usually some validator

00:57:18.990 --> 00:57:21.180
that prints a time stamp.

00:57:21.180 --> 00:57:23.400
It can be electronic as well.

00:57:23.400 --> 00:57:26.220
And what it requires
is fare inspection.

00:57:26.220 --> 00:57:29.070
So at random, a fare inspector
will board the vehicle

00:57:29.070 --> 00:57:32.580
and have a handheld device
requiring people to confirm.

00:57:32.580 --> 00:57:36.660
If it's an electronic system,
then they'll tap on here

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:39.120
and I want to make sure that
you've actually validated.

00:57:39.120 --> 00:57:41.127
If it's paper, then they
would look at the paper

00:57:41.127 --> 00:57:43.210
and make sure that you've
canceled it or validated

00:57:43.210 --> 00:57:44.970
that paper ticket.

00:57:44.970 --> 00:57:46.350
And otherwise, big fine.

00:57:46.350 --> 00:57:51.720
So the discouragement to fare
evasion is through fining

00:57:51.720 --> 00:57:53.790
and through policing.

00:57:53.790 --> 00:57:57.270
But the research shows
that there are still

00:57:57.270 --> 00:57:59.127
higher fare evasion
rates on systems

00:57:59.127 --> 00:58:00.210
that are proof of payment.

00:58:00.210 --> 00:58:06.798
People opportunistically board
and they don't pay anything.

00:58:06.798 --> 00:58:07.770
OK.

00:58:07.770 --> 00:58:08.800
Fare technology.

00:58:08.800 --> 00:58:12.310
So we've talked about
structure and policy,

00:58:12.310 --> 00:58:13.630
let's talk about technology.

00:58:13.630 --> 00:58:17.280
So this is how an AFC
system is usually set up.

00:58:17.280 --> 00:58:18.780
You have a fare engine.

00:58:18.780 --> 00:58:22.530
It's a server that has
all the fare rules in it

00:58:22.530 --> 00:58:27.300
so it can calculate fares
based on a sequence of taps.

00:58:27.300 --> 00:58:28.950
And it's connected
to different things.

00:58:28.950 --> 00:58:30.325
So a fare vending
machine, that's

00:58:30.325 --> 00:58:35.130
where you purchase your
card or your ticket.

00:58:35.130 --> 00:58:37.890
So these are usually
fiberoptic connections

00:58:37.890 --> 00:58:44.090
or hardline connections
and so they're fast.

00:58:44.090 --> 00:58:46.350
It's a real-time validation.

00:58:46.350 --> 00:58:48.810
As soon as you buy
a card and add value

00:58:48.810 --> 00:58:50.820
to it from a fare
vending machine,

00:58:50.820 --> 00:58:53.130
that balance is usually updated.

00:58:53.130 --> 00:58:56.430
If the fare engine
has a balance in it,

00:58:56.430 --> 00:58:58.140
it will be updated
in the fare engine.

00:58:58.140 --> 00:58:59.430
That's not always the case.

00:58:59.430 --> 00:59:01.620
There's many kinds of systems.

00:59:01.620 --> 00:59:04.170
So customer service
booths are also connected,

00:59:04.170 --> 00:59:06.210
fare gates are usually
connected as well.

00:59:06.210 --> 00:59:11.060
So when you tap
into a fare gate,

00:59:11.060 --> 00:59:13.690
there's a quick communication
with the fare engine saying,

00:59:13.690 --> 00:59:15.169
is this card valid, yes or no?

00:59:15.169 --> 00:59:15.960
Is there a balance?

00:59:15.960 --> 00:59:17.100
If so, deduct balance.

00:59:17.100 --> 00:59:19.470
This is how much balance
needs to be deducted.

00:59:19.470 --> 00:59:20.850
And the fare gate opens.

00:59:20.850 --> 00:59:24.960
Or maybe the fare engine
says, no, the card's not good.

00:59:24.960 --> 00:59:27.550
Sound the alarm, don't open.

00:59:27.550 --> 00:59:29.040
There are other
ways of doing it.

00:59:29.040 --> 00:59:32.190
So the card itself might hold
the balance and the fare gate

00:59:32.190 --> 00:59:35.290
might have the logic to
decide whether to open or not.

00:59:35.290 --> 00:59:39.420
But there's a whole range
of ways in which this

00:59:39.420 --> 00:59:40.900
can be configured.

00:59:40.900 --> 00:59:42.810
Fare boxes and
validators are usually

00:59:42.810 --> 00:59:47.640
on vehicles, although there
can be handheld validators.

00:59:47.640 --> 00:59:51.840
Again, a validator is more
often used for proof of payment.

00:59:51.840 --> 00:59:55.530
A fare box is used when
it's pay-as-you-go or pass,

00:59:55.530 --> 00:59:58.890
so that's what we
have here in Boston.

00:59:58.890 --> 01:00:00.300
There's two ways of doing this.

01:00:00.300 --> 01:00:03.120
It used to be the case
that they were not

01:00:03.120 --> 01:00:05.860
communicating in real
time with a fare engine.

01:00:05.860 --> 01:00:08.700
So the card and the fare
box have a little chat

01:00:08.700 --> 01:00:11.700
and decide how much
value to deduct.

01:00:11.700 --> 01:00:15.930
Later, the bus reaches the
garage or it's being cleaned

01:00:15.930 --> 01:00:18.420
and at the garage there's
a garage server that

01:00:18.420 --> 01:00:20.700
wirelessly probes the
fare box and extracts

01:00:20.700 --> 01:00:21.864
all the data from it.

01:00:21.864 --> 01:00:23.280
And only then will
the fare engine

01:00:23.280 --> 01:00:27.120
receive the information
about what transactions have

01:00:27.120 --> 01:00:28.650
been done in that fare box.

01:00:28.650 --> 01:00:33.080
So you might have, again,
a real time validation.

01:00:33.080 --> 01:00:35.680
It can be a little
slow over the air.

01:00:35.680 --> 01:00:40.740
So what happens, and this is
being done London, for example,

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:42.930
with contactless
bank cards, what

01:00:42.930 --> 01:00:47.220
happens is that maybe the
first time the card is seen,

01:00:47.220 --> 01:00:51.090
there is this dialogue
and validation.

01:00:51.090 --> 01:00:55.050
After the card is
marked as trusted,

01:00:55.050 --> 01:00:57.420
then it can just
validate immediately

01:00:57.420 --> 01:01:02.610
and the actual deduction
can wait a little bit

01:01:02.610 --> 01:01:05.250
and be sent in batches
to the fare engine.

01:01:07.950 --> 01:01:10.080
There's a cash
vault. That's where

01:01:10.080 --> 01:01:16.800
if your system accepts cash
when the bus or fare box reaches

01:01:16.800 --> 01:01:20.010
the garage, that cash
vault is taken out

01:01:20.010 --> 01:01:23.610
and the cash needs to be counted
and moved out of the fare box

01:01:23.610 --> 01:01:25.950
and to a safe place.

01:01:25.950 --> 01:01:28.710
Smart cards themselves
are computers.

01:01:28.710 --> 01:01:32.880
They are small computers
with a battery and a clock

01:01:32.880 --> 01:01:36.185
and some amount of
processing power.

01:01:36.185 --> 01:01:37.560
So they have some
memory, so they

01:01:37.560 --> 01:01:41.640
can hold some history
about your last trips.

01:01:41.640 --> 01:01:46.480
They can hold how much balance
there is in some cases.

01:01:46.480 --> 01:01:50.430
They are able to encrypt
and decrypt communication

01:01:50.430 --> 01:01:54.600
so that it's harder
to break the security

01:01:54.600 --> 01:01:57.510
and say add balance your card.

01:01:57.510 --> 01:02:00.360
And I want to add although
this is not necessarily

01:02:00.360 --> 01:02:03.150
part of the fare system,
data [INAUDIBLE]..

01:02:03.150 --> 01:02:05.610
Increasingly, we are
doing a lot of analytics.

01:02:05.610 --> 01:02:07.650
So usually, there's
some connection

01:02:07.650 --> 01:02:11.070
between the live production
system and a data warehouse

01:02:11.070 --> 01:02:14.080
where on a daily
or a weekly basis,

01:02:14.080 --> 01:02:17.170
there's an extract of data
into a data warehouse.

01:02:17.170 --> 01:02:23.790
And that allows analysts to run
heavy queries on a server that

01:02:23.790 --> 01:02:26.900
is dedicated to analysis and not
on the live system [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:26.900 --> 01:02:29.658
whether or not to open a
fare, if that makes sense.

01:02:33.465 --> 01:02:33.965
OK.

01:02:33.965 --> 01:02:35.020
Fare media.

01:02:35.020 --> 01:02:37.720
Any questions about fare
technology and the framework

01:02:37.720 --> 01:02:38.945
of how this is set up?

01:02:38.945 --> 01:02:40.570
There are lots of
variants and I didn't

01:02:40.570 --> 01:02:45.150
get into the details of
how any one system works.

01:02:45.150 --> 01:02:45.930
OK.

01:02:45.930 --> 01:02:47.220
So fare media.

01:02:47.220 --> 01:02:51.450
Cash, we all know
what that is; tokens.

01:02:51.450 --> 01:02:55.020
So I don't need to
go into how cash

01:02:55.020 --> 01:02:57.300
is minted or anything, right?

01:02:57.300 --> 01:03:02.460
So tokens are little coins
that you buy with money

01:03:02.460 --> 01:03:05.200
and it's like a
ticket in some ways.

01:03:05.200 --> 01:03:07.290
It has some value
and sometimes it's

01:03:07.290 --> 01:03:10.530
possible to be able to have
to pay two tokens for a ride,

01:03:10.530 --> 01:03:13.039
although usually it's just one.

01:03:13.039 --> 01:03:14.580
They're being phased
out because they

01:03:14.580 --> 01:03:16.950
can print paper tickets
with magnetic stripes

01:03:16.950 --> 01:03:18.350
and there's more data to it.

