01:08:31.600 --> 01:08:32.560
technology in general.

01:08:35.851 --> 01:08:36.350
All right.

01:08:36.350 --> 01:08:37.069
Smart cards.

01:08:37.069 --> 01:08:41.270
So I've already talked
a little bit about them.

01:08:41.270 --> 01:08:43.819
They enable more
complex fare structures,

01:08:43.819 --> 01:08:47.060
they allow faster boarding
and higher gatebank throughput

01:08:47.060 --> 01:08:49.520
because the validations are
much faster than a ticket.

01:08:49.520 --> 01:08:52.520
A magnetic stripe ticket
needs to be fed in

01:08:52.520 --> 01:08:54.439
and read multiple
times sometimes

01:08:54.439 --> 01:08:56.479
and it takes more
time to do that.

01:08:56.479 --> 01:08:59.330
Certainly, cash is slower.

01:08:59.330 --> 01:09:03.020
So account registration is one
of the benefits of smart cards.

01:09:03.020 --> 01:09:07.040
You don't have to do
this, but you often can.

01:09:07.040 --> 01:09:09.620
So you open an account and that
gives you balance protection.

01:09:09.620 --> 01:09:12.350
If your card is lost, you
can log into your account

01:09:12.350 --> 01:09:13.880
and remove that card.

01:09:13.880 --> 01:09:16.011
The balance could be
retained on the account

01:09:16.011 --> 01:09:18.260
so you can get a new card
associated with that account

01:09:18.260 --> 01:09:20.220
and you have your balance.

01:09:20.220 --> 01:09:22.340
Autoload is another convenience.

01:09:22.340 --> 01:09:26.090
You might have a rule that says,
if my balance drops below $5,

01:09:26.090 --> 01:09:27.500
charge $20.

01:09:27.500 --> 01:09:31.700
So if it's top up
or pay-as-you-go,

01:09:31.700 --> 01:09:35.180
then this one feature.

01:09:35.180 --> 01:09:40.939
Of course, it's much better for
us sort of researchers and data

01:09:40.939 --> 01:09:43.430
nerds, better data for
analysis and planning,

01:09:43.430 --> 01:09:45.020
longitudinal studies.

01:09:45.020 --> 01:09:46.970
You can track a
token longitudinally

01:09:46.970 --> 01:09:49.970
and understand more
about behavior.

01:09:49.970 --> 01:09:53.859
It's embeddable in employee and
student budgets, as we've seen.

01:09:53.859 --> 01:09:55.400
They are more
expensive than tickets.

01:09:55.400 --> 01:09:58.520
Now there are some smart
tickets so you can print a card

01:09:58.520 --> 01:10:00.800
with a chip circuit inside.

01:10:00.800 --> 01:10:02.660
Those are a little cheaper.

01:10:02.660 --> 01:10:06.110
One issue with smart cards is
that a lot of these systems

01:10:06.110 --> 01:10:07.370
are proprietary.

01:10:07.370 --> 01:10:09.830
And there are some standards,
but there are several

01:10:09.830 --> 01:10:11.970
standards-- too many of them--

01:10:11.970 --> 01:10:14.080
and they don't all
work everywhere

01:10:14.080 --> 01:10:16.670
and so you can't
really use a card

01:10:16.670 --> 01:10:18.470
from one system
on another system.

01:10:18.470 --> 01:10:20.130
That's usually not the case.

01:10:20.130 --> 01:10:21.770
There are some
exceptions to that.

01:10:21.770 --> 01:10:25.280
There is a move towards open
source hardware specifications.

01:10:25.280 --> 01:10:27.000
New York is a good
example of that.

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:28.970
They recently did
some procurements

01:10:28.970 --> 01:10:32.670
where they asked all
the parts to be--

01:10:32.670 --> 01:10:35.120
it was for an AVL
system in this case--

01:10:35.120 --> 01:10:40.380
to be open source hardware
and communications technology.

01:10:40.380 --> 01:10:42.720
That means they're not
locked into that vendor.

01:10:42.720 --> 01:10:47.780
So if they need to replace
one aspect of that system,

01:10:47.780 --> 01:10:50.090
they can hire someone
else that also

01:10:50.090 --> 01:10:52.760
complies with that standard
and that part can be replaced.

01:10:52.760 --> 01:10:56.270
That lowers costs,
increases competition,

01:10:56.270 --> 01:10:58.855
and it means again that they're
not locked into that vendor.

01:10:58.855 --> 01:10:59.354
Lee.

01:10:59.354 --> 01:11:01.904
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] security
at all or [INAUDIBLE]..

01:11:01.904 --> 01:11:03.820
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
Usually, the systems

01:11:03.820 --> 01:11:05.990
have strong standard encryption.

01:11:05.990 --> 01:11:08.180
Part of the standard is
what encryption is used

01:11:08.180 --> 01:11:14.480
and what encryption algorithms
are used, hashing, et cetera.

01:11:14.480 --> 01:11:14.990
Yeah.

01:11:14.990 --> 01:11:17.840
So the Charlie card has
pretty weak encryption,

01:11:17.840 --> 01:11:25.390
40 bits I think, and the
same key on every card.

01:11:25.390 --> 01:11:28.930
So a long time ago, someone
cracked the key by brute force

01:11:28.930 --> 01:11:31.000
and that's the same key
on every Charlie card.

01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:34.300
So once that key is public,
anyone with the equipment

01:11:34.300 --> 01:11:38.080
could load a fake
balance to the card

01:11:38.080 --> 01:11:41.770
because the cards are the ones
having the balance in the AFC

01:11:41.770 --> 01:11:44.470
system here and not
the fare engine.

01:11:44.470 --> 01:11:47.290
That means that effectively,
you can lie to the fare system

01:11:47.290 --> 01:11:50.620
and say that you have
more money than you have.

01:11:50.620 --> 01:11:53.380
Much harder to do with
any modern system,

01:11:53.380 --> 01:11:55.210
certainly contact
with a bank card

01:11:55.210 --> 01:11:57.730
which has a very strong
encryption and unique keys

01:11:57.730 --> 01:11:58.909
per card.

01:11:58.909 --> 01:12:00.950
AUDIENCE: Did MIT students
get caught doing that?

01:12:00.950 --> 01:12:02.700
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ:
The MIT students

01:12:02.700 --> 01:12:04.540
were the first to do this.

01:12:04.540 --> 01:12:08.120
They were caught and
there was some issue.

01:12:08.120 --> 01:12:10.650
Which I think it ended up
being just a slap on the wrist,

01:12:10.650 --> 01:12:15.557
but there was a lot
of issue with it.

01:12:15.557 --> 01:12:17.140
Because they wanted
to publish a paper

01:12:17.140 --> 01:12:20.000
or publish something and
then that was an issue.

01:12:20.000 --> 01:12:20.500
OK.

01:12:20.500 --> 01:12:24.410
So integration across agencies
of a region is possible.

01:12:24.410 --> 01:12:28.160
That's one of the reasons for
moving towards smart cards,

01:12:28.160 --> 01:12:31.030
especially in regions
that have many providers.

01:12:31.030 --> 01:12:33.100
But it's challenging, and
usually the challenges

01:12:33.100 --> 01:12:37.190
are less technical and more
about trust and business

01:12:37.190 --> 01:12:40.420
and who gets to decide
what color the card is

01:12:40.420 --> 01:12:44.314
or exactly what the
fare policy will be.

01:12:44.314 --> 01:12:45.730
This is another
interesting thing.

01:12:45.730 --> 01:12:49.540
In some countries, and
I'm thinking specifically

01:12:49.540 --> 01:12:53.980
of Japan and China, there
are examples of retail stores

01:12:53.980 --> 01:12:55.960
that have partnered
with a transit agency

01:12:55.960 --> 01:13:00.707
and you can use the card
at retail locations.

01:13:00.707 --> 01:13:02.040
Hong Kong is an example of that.

01:13:02.040 --> 01:13:06.880
There's more than 100 retail
locations that accept Octopus.

01:13:06.880 --> 01:13:10.570
And in Japan, I know that
there are entire cities where

01:13:10.570 --> 01:13:13.600
there's like a whole mall and
this is what most people use

01:13:13.600 --> 01:13:15.160
as a charge card.

01:13:15.160 --> 01:13:18.490
So that's interesting.

01:13:18.490 --> 01:13:21.100
If you don't have very
tough privacy laws,

01:13:21.100 --> 01:13:23.780
as you do in Europe and the US--

01:13:23.780 --> 01:13:25.750
I'm not sure what
they are in Japan,

01:13:25.750 --> 01:13:28.420
but there was some
research where

01:13:28.420 --> 01:13:33.130
they were combining all the
data from shopping and transit

01:13:33.130 --> 01:13:38.110
to get really interesting
behavioral analytics.

01:13:38.110 --> 01:13:39.790
And you can do
interesting things

01:13:39.790 --> 01:13:46.290
like offer discounts at stores
if you do something in transit.

01:13:46.290 --> 01:13:51.295
So there's a lot of very
interesting [INAUDIBLE]..

01:13:51.295 --> 01:13:53.346
AUDIENCE: Our company
did the same thing

01:13:53.346 --> 01:13:55.796
and once [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:00.075 --> 01:14:04.264
So after that, we are
very careful about dealing

01:14:04.264 --> 01:14:05.169
with [INAUDIBLE].

01:14:05.169 --> 01:14:06.460
GABRIEL SANCHEZ-MARTINEZ: Yeah.

01:14:06.460 --> 01:14:07.680
Yeah.

01:14:07.680 --> 01:14:10.200
Thanks for sharing.

01:14:10.200 --> 01:14:11.400
So contactless bank cards.

01:14:11.400 --> 01:14:12.899
We started talking
about this, we've

01:14:12.899 --> 01:14:14.430
mentioned that multiple times.

01:14:14.430 --> 01:14:16.560
Here's the logic for it.

01:14:16.560 --> 01:14:18.090
A transit agency
would prefer not

01:14:18.090 --> 01:14:20.550
having to deal with the
complexities and costs of fare

01:14:20.550 --> 01:14:21.776
collection.

01:14:21.776 --> 01:14:23.400
Essentially, if you
have a fare system,

01:14:23.400 --> 01:14:26.320
it's like having a small bank.

01:14:26.320 --> 01:14:28.890
It doesn't give out loans,
it doesn't do other things

01:14:28.890 --> 01:14:30.780
that banks do, but
you are dealing

01:14:30.780 --> 01:14:33.570
with money and the cards
and customer service related

01:14:33.570 --> 01:14:36.150
to cards and all those things.

01:14:36.150 --> 01:14:37.950
Banks do that, and
they do it very well.

01:14:37.950 --> 01:14:42.840
So why not outsource that
part of the business to banks?

01:14:42.840 --> 01:14:46.780
There are multiple banks so
they can get competition.

01:14:46.780 --> 01:14:50.190
So credit card companies
specialize in payment;

01:14:50.190 --> 01:14:52.380
contactless bank
cards are very secure,

01:14:52.380 --> 01:14:55.950
much more so than
say the Charlie card;

01:14:55.950 --> 01:14:59.860
you can use cards like
this in several ways.

01:14:59.860 --> 01:15:03.150
So you could directly
use them for payment

01:15:03.150 --> 01:15:05.070
as you would at
a retail location

01:15:05.070 --> 01:15:09.570
or you can use the token that
identifies that card, tying it

01:15:09.570 --> 01:15:10.890
to an account.

01:15:10.890 --> 01:15:14.460
And then your fare engine can
calculate what the fare will be

01:15:14.460 --> 01:15:15.990
and capping and all that.

01:15:15.990 --> 01:15:21.270
And then on a
regular basis, there

01:15:21.270 --> 01:15:25.050
would be a charge to your
credit card or account

01:15:25.050 --> 01:15:29.940
for whatever total
was calculated.

01:15:29.940 --> 01:15:34.140
So that also enables
Apple Pay and Android Pay.

01:15:34.140 --> 01:15:36.580
If you can put your
credit card on your phone,

01:15:36.580 --> 01:15:40.350
then you can use your phone
to get into the system.

01:15:40.350 --> 01:15:43.110
In London, people love that.

01:15:43.110 --> 01:15:44.860
It reduces fare
collection costs.

01:15:44.860 --> 01:15:47.610
So why?

01:15:47.610 --> 01:15:49.770
Not necessarily obvious.

01:15:49.770 --> 01:15:52.050
So it simplifies
customer communication.

01:15:52.050 --> 01:15:55.260
You don't have to issue
new cards to people,

01:15:55.260 --> 01:15:59.310
you don't have to explain
how you pay because people

01:15:59.310 --> 01:16:01.500
know how to use cards.

01:16:01.500 --> 01:16:03.150
It relies on open
standards so there's

01:16:03.150 --> 01:16:04.660
more competition on the market.

01:16:04.660 --> 01:16:06.780
There's several
banks, for example,

01:16:06.780 --> 01:16:10.980
and you could have
banks compete for who

01:16:10.980 --> 01:16:16.140
will give you a better deal in
terms of fees on these cards.

01:16:19.080 --> 01:16:21.480
It outsources some aspects
of customer service to banks.

01:16:21.480 --> 01:16:23.340
So if my card stopped
working, who's

01:16:23.340 --> 01:16:27.630
going to get the phone call,
the transit agency or the bank?

01:16:27.630 --> 01:16:30.570
And it eliminates costs of sort
of creating and distributing

01:16:30.570 --> 01:16:31.380
smart cards.

01:16:31.380 --> 01:16:35.250
So there's several ways in
which this is reducing costs.

01:16:35.250 --> 01:16:39.580
London has successfully
been able to reduce

01:16:39.580 --> 01:16:46.950
the number of station attendants
and especially of booths

01:16:46.950 --> 01:16:49.580
where they sell Oyster cards and
have customer service related

01:16:49.580 --> 01:16:50.540
to Oyster cards.

01:16:50.540 --> 01:16:53.726
They've been able to close
those and save money.

01:16:53.726 --> 01:16:55.100
And then there's
an equity issue,

01:16:55.100 --> 01:16:57.420
and this is what is
always sort of brought up

01:16:57.420 --> 01:16:59.750
when you talk about
contactless bank cards, which

01:16:59.750 --> 01:17:01.580
is what about the unbanked?

01:17:01.580 --> 01:17:06.120
The poorest people are the ones
who don't have a bank account.

01:17:06.120 --> 01:17:08.120
So what can you do about that?

01:17:08.120 --> 01:17:10.340
Does that make this not work?

01:17:10.340 --> 01:17:13.160
So there are multiple
ways of addressing that.

01:17:13.160 --> 01:17:16.520
An agency can issue cards
that have preloaded balance.

01:17:16.520 --> 01:17:20.510
So that person could interact
with the agency, not the bank.

01:17:20.510 --> 01:17:23.030
They don't necessarily
need a bank account.

01:17:23.030 --> 01:17:25.240
You can have banks
offer free accounts.

01:17:25.240 --> 01:17:26.780
So you can try to
encourage people

01:17:26.780 --> 01:17:30.500
to open accounts that have
no fee, no minimum balance.

01:17:30.500 --> 01:17:34.830
So some [INAUDIBLE] special
accounts created for that.

01:17:34.830 --> 01:17:36.800
And one other issue
is that you must

01:17:36.800 --> 01:17:40.310
be able to obtain these
cards at many locations.

01:17:40.310 --> 01:17:43.520
If you move towards
a system like this

01:17:43.520 --> 01:17:47.630
and you can only get one
of these sort of equity

01:17:47.630 --> 01:17:54.380
issued cards if you want from
one station downtown, that

01:17:54.380 --> 01:17:58.580
means that the person who
depends on two or three buses

01:17:58.580 --> 01:18:02.450
to get into downtown
can't easily get a card.

01:18:02.450 --> 01:18:05.600
So you must be able
to maybe get these

01:18:05.600 --> 01:18:08.390
at several retail
locations or have

01:18:08.390 --> 01:18:13.980
fare vending machines
in multiple places,

01:18:13.980 --> 01:18:17.510
especially in zones of high
concentrations of people

01:18:17.510 --> 01:18:22.960
that depend on transit and
don't have bank accounts.

01:18:22.960 --> 01:18:23.860
OK.

01:18:23.860 --> 01:18:27.800
So there are ways of
dealing with that.

01:18:27.800 --> 01:18:31.119
Boston is considering now
what they call AFC 2.0.

01:18:31.119 --> 01:18:32.660
They're sort of
branding it that way.

01:18:32.660 --> 01:18:37.100
And they're probably
going to be moving forward

01:18:37.100 --> 01:18:41.840
with the London model of
using contactless bank cards.

01:18:41.840 --> 01:18:43.910
So we'll see how it
plays out and we'll

01:18:43.910 --> 01:18:47.210
see what that does to the
payment industry in general

01:18:47.210 --> 01:18:52.590
in the US in terms of that means
more people will have these.

01:18:52.590 --> 01:18:57.710
Does that mean that a lot of
readers at retail locations

01:18:57.710 --> 01:19:01.050
will start accepting that,
and what will that do?

01:19:01.050 --> 01:19:01.910
It's a question.

01:19:01.910 --> 01:19:04.620
We'll see what happens.

01:19:04.620 --> 01:19:05.310
